outlooksByWeek.1: Amon-Ra St. Brown has seen his production rise steadily each season since being drafted in 2021, setting career highs in catches, yards, targets, and touchdowns last year. He accounted for nearly 30 percent of the Lions' targets in 2023, finishing in the top-five league-wide in each category. With star rookie TE Sam LaPorta and other receivers in the mix, St. Brown remains the primary pass-catching option, excelling in both short-area and yards-after-catch situations. He faces a Rams defense in Week 1 that allowed 246.8 passing yards per game last season, ranking 20th in the NFL. St. Brown's significant target share and consistent performance make him an elite fantasy option each week, regardless of the matchup.
outlooksByWeek.2: Amon-Ra St. Brown had a surprisingly muted performance in the season opener, catching just three passes for 13 yards on six targets in Detroit's 26-20 overtime victory over the Rams. The 24-year-old WR was overshadowed by Jameson Williams and a dominant ground game. St. Brown exceeded 90 yards in 11 of 16 games last season, making his slow start an anomaly rather than a trend. Looking ahead to Week 2, St. Brown faces the Buccaneers, who allowed the second-fewest receiving yards to WRs in their opener; however, this was partly due to QB Jayden Daniels' frequent scrambles. With Tampa Bay's secondary struggling with injuries and ranking 25th in fantasy points allowed to WRs last season, St. Brown is poised for a significant rebound.
outlooksByWeek.3: Amon-Ra St. Brown is dealing with a leg contusion and cramping after exiting late in last week's game, but he's expected to be available for Week 3 against the Cardinals. Despite the injury, St. Brown had a strong performance in Week 2, catching 11 passes for 119 yards on 19 targets. He was heavily targeted after a quieter Week 1 and should remain a central figure in the Lions' offense. Arizona's defense has allowed 10.0 yards per target to opposing wide receivers this season, which is the third-highest in the league. If St. Brown is at full strength, he could take advantage of this matchup and continue his prominent role in the Detroit offense.
outlooksByWeek.4: Amon-Ra St. Brown has rebounded strongly since a disappointing performance in the season opener, catching 18 of 26 targets for 194 yards and a touchdown over Detroit's last two games. While there were concerns that the emergence of fellow wideout Jameson Williams might cut into St. Brown's target share, those worries have subsided for now. In Week 4, St. Brown will face a stingy Seahawks secondary that has limited opposing wide receivers to just 4.8 yards per target this season, the second-best mark in the league.
outlooksByWeek.6: Amon-Ra St. Brown and the Lions return from a bye to take on the Cowboys in Week 6. The star wide receiver's yardage totals have been somewhat disappointing through the early portion of the 2024 campaign - he had just 45 yards against the Seahawks in Week 4 - but St. Brown has nonetheless managed to make a clear impact with his opportunities. St. Brown scored his second receiving TD of the year Week 4 and also threw a seven-yard touchdown pass to quarterback Jared Goff. Across 16 regular-season appearances in 2023, St. Brown averaged 94.7 receiving yards per game, a mark that has declined to 63 yards per game early in the 2024 season. Coming off the bye, St. Brown and offensive coordinator Ben Johnson will look to collaborate on more consistent receiving production going forward.
outlooksByWeek.7: Amon-Ra St. Brown will continue to lead a dominant Lions passing attack as the team faces off against a stalwart Vikings defense in Week 7. Due to Detroit getting out to an early lead during the team's blowout 47-9 win over the Cowboys, St. Brown saw just four targets, his lowest total of the season. He made the most of those opportunities, securing all four looks for 37 yards and a score, but too positive a game script for the Lions limited St. Brown's overall upside. The Vikings have allowed the sixth fewest passing yards per attempt to opposing teams in the NFL, but a more competitive contest could nonetheless result in St. Brown improving on his total production levels. In four straight games, St. Brown has either found the end zone or surpassed the 100-yard mark, but the emergence of Jameson Williams as a true playmaker, combined with quarterback Jared Goff's willingness to spread the ball around, has resulted in a lessened target share for St. Brown. He's averaging 8.4 targets per game thus far, as opposed to the 10.18 targets per game he commanded during the 2023 regular season.
outlooksByWeek.8: Amon-Ra St. Brown will continue to lead Detroit's receiving corps as the NFC North's top seed hosts the Titans at home in Week 8. The star wideout was perfect during the Lions' pivotal 31-29 win over Minnesota, securing all eight of his targets for 112 yards and a score. Living up to form, St. Brown led Detroit in receptions, receiving yards and targets versus the Vikings, eclipsing the century mark for the second time this season. The star wideout has now scored in four consecutive games, and a home matchup against a Tennessee defense fresh off allowing 34 points to the Bills puts St. Brown in a prime position to continue his streak.
outlooksByWeek.9: Amon-Ra St. Brown will look to bounce back in Week 9 as the Lions travel to Green Bay for a key divisional matchup. Detroit's offense had no issues imposing its will versus Tennessee in Week 8, a 52-14 win in the Lions' favor, but St. Brown was so effectively utilized as a decoy in the contest that his number rarely had to be truly dialed up. The star wide receiver logged two catches for seven yards and one touchdown, salvaging his performance against the Titans with a score, while demanding enough coverage attention that both Kalif Raymond and Brock Wright were able to get into the end zone themselves. With No. 2 wideout Jameson Williams (suspension) still not yet available in what should be a more competitive matchup against the Packers, Amon-Ra figures to be featured in his more typical role as the clear leader of Detroit's passing game.
outlooksByWeek.10: Amon-Ra St. Brown will look to keep his six-game touchdown streak alive as the Lions travel to Houston in Week 10. Rainy conditions combined with a game script that saw Detroit nursing a lead limited St. Brown's opportunities during Detroit's win over Green Bay, with which the team solidified its position atop the NFC North standings. Nonetheless, St. Brown finished with a solid 56 yards and one touchdown while bringing in all seven of his targets. St. Brown and quarterback Jared Goff will return to a more comfortable dome environment Week 10, and have the benefit of facing a Texans secondary that just surrendered three touchdowns combined to Jets wideouts Garrett Wilson and Davante Adams.
outlooksByWeek.11: Amon-Ra St. Brown will look to extend his seven-game touchdown streak as the Lions take on the Jaguars in Week 11. Despite Jared Goff throwing a career-high five INTs during Detroit's narrow 26-23 win over Houston, St. Brown finished with a respectable statline. He reeled in six of eight targets for 60 yards and a score, a seventh straight game in which St. Brown has hauled in exactly one receiving touchdown. The star wideout has racked up an impressive 54-524-7 receiving line across nine appearances so far, putting him on pace for a career-best year in terms of scoring, but to fall short of the 1,515 yards he racked up during the 2023 regular season. A matchup against Jacksonville's secondary, which ranks 30th against the pass, puts St. Brown in a good spot to keep up his momentum.
outlooksByWeek.12: Amon-Ra St. Brown will continue leading Detroit's wide receiver corps as the team prepares for a favorable Week 12 road matchup against the Colts. The star wideout is coming off a perfect performance during the Lions' lopsided 52-6 win over Jacksonville, in which he secured all 11 of his targets for 161 yards and two touchdowns. St. Brown also rushed once for a loss of four yards. In addition to extending his touchdown streak to a total of eight games, the Detroit superstar posted his first multi-touchdown effort of the 2024 campaign versus the hapless Jaguars' secondary, while also posting his highest yardage total of the year. St. Brown has now exceeded 100 receiving yards in three of 10 appearances and will benefit from a matchup against Indianapolis' secondary, which ranks just 26th against the pass.
outlooksByWeek.13: Amon-Ra St. Brown will continue to lead Detroit's passing attack as the team prepares for a Thanksgiving day divisional matchup against Chicago in Week 13. The star wideout had his eight-game TD streak broken during the Lions' 24-6 win over Indianapolis, but he remained productive with six catches for 62 yards. St. Brown has now logged six or more targets in four straight games, but keeping up his momentum against the Bears' impressive secondary will be no easy feat. Chicago is fresh off having limited Justin Jefferson to just 27 yards in an overtime loss to the Vikings, and the team could again deploy a defensive scheme that prioritizes removing Jared Goff's No. 1 receiver.
outlooksByWeek.14: Amon-Ra St. Brown and the Lions will look to remain in clear control of the NFC North heading into a Week 14 divisional tilt against the Packers. That will be Detroit's second consecutive Thursday game, as the team is coming off a narrow 23-20 win over the Bears. As per usual, St. Brown led the Lions in receiving versus Chicago with five catches for 73 yards on seven targets, though it was TE Sam LaPorta who accounted for both of Jared Goff's passing touchdowns. St. Brown will continue to work as the clear lead man in what's normally been a prolific passing game for Detroit, and an offense that ranks 1st in points per game. If Packers cornerback Jaire Alexander (knee), who missed Week 13, remains anything less than full health, it will bode well for St. Brown's chances of thriving against Green Bay's secondary.
outlooksByWeek.15: Amon-Ra St. Brown will look to bounce back as the Lions host the 10-3 Bills in Week 15. The standout receiver was quiet during last Thursday's narrow 34-31 win over the Packers, with just five catches for 43 yards on six targets. St. Brown did post a 10-yard run on his only carry, but the contest was nonetheless his first since Week 1 finishing with less than 50 receiving yards and no touchdowns. St. Brown figures to resume operating as the focal point of Detroit's aerial attack versus Buffalo, but he won't have a favorable matchup as he works to rebound. Buffalo ranks 9th against the pass but are fresh off a loss to the Rams, in which they allowed 12 catches,162 yards and a touchdown to Puka Nacua.

player.seasonOutlook: After inking a new 4-year contract this offseason, St. Brown returns as the leader of the Lions' receiving corps. One of most consistent wide receivers in fantasy, ARSB had an outstanding 11 games with at least 18 fantasy points in 2023. No wide receiver had more top-20 weekly finishes and only Tyreek Hill had more weeks finishing seventh or better. Possessing both a high floor and ceiling, St. Brown was top five in every major receiving category last season and returns to an offense that looks to be just as potent this season. St. Brown is showing no signs of slowing down, and is poised to be a top-five fantasy wide receiver in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jahmyr Gibbs enters his second season as the Lions' lead back after a strong rookie year, showcasing his ability as both a runner (5.2 YPC, 10 TDs) and a receiver. With David Montgomery likely serving as the 1B option, Gibbs is positioned to be the primary playmaker in the backfield. Detroit's excellent offensive line will continue to create opportunities, though Gibbs might see fewer goal-line carries due to Montgomery's power-running role. In Week 1, Gibbs faces a Rams defense that was tough against the run last season, allowing only 77.5 rushing yards per game to opposing RBs, ranking 8th in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jahmyr Gibbs continues to be a key dual-threat in the Lions' offense, combining 11 carries with four catches in last week's win over the Rams. He averaged 11.8 carries and 2.7 catches over the team's final nine games last season when both he and David Montgomery were healthy, producing 77.5 total yards per game with exactly nine touchdowns during that span. While it's slightly discouraging that he didn't see more work in the opener, Gibbs should remain productive with his touches moving forward. Detroit faces a Buccaneers defense in Week 2 that allowed 138 rushing yards last week, with most coming from QB Jayden Daniels. Tampa Bay was stingy against opposing backfields last season, ranking 9th in the NFL in yards per carry allowed to running backs (3.94) and 5th in yards per target to running backs (5.03).
outlooksByWeek.3: Jahmyr Gibbs will look to maintain his prominent role in the Lions' backfield despite sharing duties with David Montgomery as they head into Week 3 against the Cardinals. In last week's loss to the Buccaneers, Gibbs totaled 20 touches, rushing for 84 yards and catching seven passes for 22 yards. He out-gained Montgomery by 49 rushing yards and had a larger share of the running back targets, although Montgomery scored a short-yardage touchdown. Against an Arizona defense allowing 3.3 yards per carry (5th in the NFL) and 6.64 yards per target to running backs (23rd in the NFL), Gibbs has a good chance to shine in the passing game this week.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jahmyr Gibbs heads into a Week 4 matchup with the Seahawks, averaging 94.3 total yards on 17.0 touches through Detroit's first three games. The sophomore back has surpassed 100 total yards in consecutive contests after achieving this feat five times last season. While David Montgomery continues to handle the short-yardage duties, limiting Gibbs' scoring upside, he has still managed to rack up 13 total touchdowns across his last 14 games dating back to last year. Gibbs will look to maintain his momentum against a Seahawks defense that has allowed running backs to gain 4.3 yards per carry, ranking 16th in the NFL this year. However, Seattle has limited opposing running backs to just 2.9 yards per target, which leads the league.
outlooksByWeek.6: Jahmyr Gibbs will look to keep up his momentum in the running game as Detroit prepares for a Week 6 matchup against the Cowboys. The dynamic second-year pro has scored four times in as many games to kick off the 2024 regular season and is averaging an excellent 5.3 yards per carry. Gibbs has just 76 receiving yards on the season, demonstrating that his usage in the passing game hasn't exactly lived up to projections, but he's nonetheless averaging just over 100 scrimmage yards per contest. Both Gibbs and backfield mate David Montgomery have logged double-digit rush attempts in each of the Lions games this season, so a week of rest could benefit both versus a Dallas defense that ranks bottom-10 against the run.
outlooksByWeek.7: Jahmyr Gibbs will continue splitting work out of the backfield with David Montgomery as the Lions take on the undefeated Vikings on the road in Week 7. Montgomery overshadowed Gibbs due to his scoring twice on the ground during Detroit's 47-9 blowout win over Dallas, but Gibbs was better as a receiver, securing three of five targets for 28 yards. Gibbs has shown a proclivity for the end zone of his own, having scored four times in five games this season, but Montgomery continues to dominate goal-line work for the Lions. Montgomery has scored in eight consecutive regular-season games, but both of Detroit's tailbacks have been remarkably efficient, having each compiled 70-plus yards from scrimmage in each game of the 2024 campaign. Now, Gibbs and Montgomery face the task of overcoming a Minnesota defense that's allowed the fewest total rushing yards in the NFL, with only the Ravens boasting a lower YPC allowed to opponents.
outlooksByWeek.8: Jahmyr Gibbs will look to follow up a 160-yard, two-TD performance versus the Titans at home in Week 8, as the Lions work to stay atop the NFC North divisional standings. With David Montgomery having missed time in the first half of Detroit's 31-29 win over the Vikings, Gibbs took over as the Lions' clear backfield leader, to the tune of 15 carries for 116 yards and two touchdowns. He also corralled all four of his targets for 44 yards, displaying his usual elite versatility. Gibbs has now scored multiple touchdowns in two of his last three appearances, and he'll be positioned to benefit from a potential blowout at home against Tennessee.
outlooksByWeek.9: Jahmyr Gibbs will continue working alongside David Montromgery to form arguably the NFL's most dangerous backfield as the Lions travel to Green Bay for a key Week 9 divisional matchup. Detroit is fresh off a Week 8 blowout win over Tennessee in which Gibbs rushed 11 times for 127 yards and a score, while Montgomery logged nine carries for 33 yards and a score of his own. Gibbs has now exceeded 100 yards on the ground in back-to-back games, putting him at an outstanding 6.4 YPC mark on the season. The second-year pro's elite efficiency and big-play ability make him an ideal complement for Montgomery's bruising rushing style, so while neither have path to the 20-touch mark that a true workhorse role might entail, together Gibbs and Montgomery continue to demonstrate that they're greater than the sum of their parts. Against a Packers defense allowing the 10th fewest rushing yards per game, Gibbs may have to show out as a pass-catcher in order to truly thrive.
outlooksByWeek.10: Jahmyr Gibbs has now scored in three consecutive games and will look to keep up his momentum as the Lions head on the road to Houston in Week 10. He rushed 11 times for 65 yards and a touchdown during a rainy 24-14 win in Lambeau Field, adding one catch for 11 yards on two targets. It was David Montgomery who Detroit leaned on most due to a positive game script and muddy weather, but Gibbs' explosive score on the Loins' first drive of the second half set him up for the more prolific day. Gibbs has now tallied eight touchdowns in as many appearances this season. The Lions now return to a dome environment on the road against Houston, a game that could again see Detroit nurse a comfortable lead, pending the Texans' tentative return of Nico Collins (hamstring) from IR.
outlooksByWeek.11: Jahmyr Gibbs carries plenty of momentum into Detroit's Week 11 road matchup against the Jaguars. The offense as a whole struggled uncharacteristically during the Lions' narrow 26-23 win over the Texans, with QB Jared Goff's usual accuracy vanishing and resulting in five interceptions, but Gibbs remained a clear bright spot. Courtesy of 21 touches (compared to David Montgomery's 13), Gibbs rushed 19 times for 71 yards and secured two of three passes for 37 yards. It was Montgomery who punched in Detroit's only rushing score of the game, which came in a short-yardage situation, but Gibbs was the only skill-position player on either franchise to rack up 100-plus yards from scrimmage. He and Montgomery now both face what looks like a tremendous matchup against a reeling Jacksonville squad.
outlooksByWeek.12: Jahmyr Gibbs will continue to work alongside David Montgomery out of the backfield as the Lions head to Indianapolis for a Week 12 road matchup. Together, Gibbs and Montgomery form what's been the most potent thunder-and-lightning RB duo in the league, with the two having combined for over 200 yards from scrimmage during Detroit's 52-6 trouncing of the Jaguars. For his part, Gibbs rushed 11 times for 69 yards and a score plus one 54-yard catch, while Montgomery had 15 carries for 75 yards and two TDs, in addition to 20 yards on three catches. Gibbs has scored five rushing touchdowns in his last five appearances and exceeded 100 yards from scrimmage six times on the season, and a matchup against the Colts, who rank 28th against the rush, could again put him in ideal position for success.
outlooksByWeek.13: Jahmyr Gibbs and the Lions will look to retain their firm first place lead in the NFC North heading into a Week 13 matchup against the fourth place Bears. The Thanksgiving day matchup will be an opportunity for Gibbs - who has scored seven rushing touchdowns in his last six appearances - to thrive on a primetime stage. Gibbs is already up to 10 rushing scores on the year, matching his previous career-high mark from 2023, despite having logged just one TD in the receiving game. He notably outproduced backfield mate David Montgomery during Detroit's 24-6 win over Indianapolis, with a 21-90-2 rushing line while Montgomery went 8-37-1. The final split was heavily influenced by Montgomery exiting in the third quarter with a shoulder injury, but if both backs are available to play Thursday, Gibbs and Montgomery could both thrive against a Chicago defense that ranks 20th against the run but has allowed the third-fewest passing touchdowns to opponents.
outlooksByWeek.14: Jahmyr Gibbs will work to avoid any sloppiness in Week 14 against the Packers, a game that will be Detroit's second consecutive divisional matchup on a Thursday. During the Lions' narrow win over the Bears on Thanksgiving, Gibbs was excessively efficient, turning nine carries into just 87 yards - nearly the 88 yards that David Montgomery managed on 21 rushes. A fumble in the red zone may have factored into Gibbs ending the day with just 11 touches (also catching two of four targets for 17 yards). Green Bay has been solid against the run, allowing just 106.6 yards per game (8th in the NFL), but both Gibbs and Montgomery will be plenty involved for the Lions in what may shape up to be a crucial battle for the fate of the NFC North. Detroit sits comfortably in first place of the vision with an 11-1 record, but at 9-3 it isn't as though Green Bay is definitively in the rear view.
outlooksByWeek.15: Jahmyr Gibbs will continue working as the 'lightning' to David Montgomery's 'thunder' as the Lions prepare for a difficult home matchup against the Bills in Week 15. Both Gibbs (15 carries for 43 yards) and Montgomery (14 carries for 51 yards and a score) were contained on the ground during last Thursday's narrow divisional win over the Packers, but it was Gibbs who secured one of Jared Goff's three passing touchdowns. Both Gibbs and Montgomery were effective through the passing game and secured all of their targets, posting 6-30-1 and 5-33-0 receiving lines, respectively. Next, Gibbs and Montgomery will face the task of overcoming a 10-3 Buffalo team.

player.seasonOutlook: Gibbs dispelled any draft-day doubts by finishing as fantasy's RB10 in his rookie season. The 12th overall pick in 2023 showcased his explosiveness in a Lions offense that had the second-most RB rushing yards and attempts. Gibbs had six weeks inside the top three at RB, finished second in yards before first contact and was fifth in fantasy points per touch. Despite being in a committee with David Montgomery, Gibbs was also 12th in scrimmage yards, ninth in total touchdowns and top 10 in targets and receptions. All this while ranking 25th among RBs in touches. He won't have the workload of a feature back, but at just 22 years old, Gibbs is already a superstar and should be viewed as a clear top-10 RB.

outlooksByWeek.1: Marvin Harrison will make his debut for the Cardinals in Week 1 at Buffalo, who were the NFL's sixth best passing defense last year. Harrison is one of the most highly-rated wide receiver prospects ever, and he projects to immediately become Kyler Murray's number one receiving option. He should see plenty of targets in this game, especially if the talented Buffalo offense forces the Cardinals to throw more frequently in a negative game script. Harrison will have a tough task on his hands in his first start facing coverage from talented Bills cornerback duo Taron Johnson and Rasul Douglas. The Bills defense had 16 interceptions and held opponents under 220 receiving yards per game last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Marvin Harrison makes his home debut in Week 2 as the Cardinals take on the Rams. Harrison struggled last weekend against the Bills secondary, and he was held to just one reception for 4 receiving yards. Cardinals' coach Jonathan Gannon said he wants to get Harrison more involved in the offense this weekend, and he'll certainly have a more favorable matchup. The Rams' secondary is one of the league's weaker units after losing Jalen Ramsey this offseason, and they are coming off of a Week 1 tilt against the Lions where they allowed 217 receiving yards, 12th most in the league.
outlooksByWeek.3: Marvin Harrison had a massive performance over the weekend after a poor Week 1 debut, and he caught two touchdowns and four of his eight targets for 130 receiving yards. Harrison's eight targets led the Cardinals, and he showed off his speed and big play ability with his 60-yard touchdown catch in the first quarter. Even with Trey McBride taking up targets, Harrison should see plenty of targets in the Cardinals offense moving forward. In Week 3, Arizona goes up against a Detroit passing defense that has struggled early this season despite some offseason improvements. The Lions have allowed 251 receiving yards per game in 2024, sixth most in the league.
outlooksByWeek.4: Marvin Harrison caught five passes over the weekend for 64 yards and a touchdown. Harrison led Arizona with 10 targets, which was the second week in a row that the rookie led the offense in targets. Harrison has bounced back nicely after a horrible debut performance in Week 1, and he has logged nine receptions for 194 yards and three touchdowns in his past two games. In Week 4, Harrison and the Cardinals face off against a Commanders passing defense that has struggled so far in 2024. Washington is allowing more than 250 passing yards per game in 2024, making them one of the worst passing defenses in the league.
outlooksByWeek.5: Marvin Harrison continued his scoring surge in Week 4, hauling in his fourth touchdown in the last three games during a blowout loss to the Commanders. The fourth overall pick in the 2024 NFL Draft has quickly become Kyler Murray's top downfield option, accumulating a 14-239-4 line in those three contests on 25 targets. Harrison has yet to catch more than five passes in a game, so there's still significant upside in his profile if the Cardinals' offense takes a step forward. Harrison will face a 49ers secondary in Week 5 that's been vulnerable to big plays so far, sitting 20th in receiving yards allowed to wideouts despite being tied for ninth in catches allowed to the position.
outlooksByWeek.6: Marvin Harrison ranked second on Arizona with seven targets, but he only recorded two receptions for 36 yards over the weekend. Harrison's catch rate is below 50 percent in his rookie campaign, which is well below the league average. While Harrison needs to improve his efficiency, he continues to lead Arizona's wide receivers in snaps and routes run. He stands to continue to be targeted heavily by Kyler Murray in Arizona's Week 6 matchup against the Packers. Green Bay has allowed 232 passing yards per game this season, ranking 23rd in the league.
outlooksByWeek.7: Marvin Harrison is questionable for Arizona's Week 7 game against the Chargers after suffering a concussion over the weekend. Harrison had only played eight snaps before he got hurt, and he failed to catch both of his targets. If Harrison is unable to clear the concussion protocol, Michael Wilson will likely move into the top spot on Arizona's wide receiver depth chart. The Chargers have allowed 192 passing yards per game in 2024, eighth best in the league.
outlooksByWeek.8: Marvin Harrison continued to be inefficient in Week 7, catching three of his six targets for 21 yards. Harrison has a high average depth of target, but his 45 percent catch rate this season is still quite low and one of the reasons he's been so inconsistent in fantasy. On the bright side, Harrison led Arizona's wide receivers in offensive snaps played, and his six targets were second best on the team behind Trey McBride. In Week 8, Harrison and the Cardinals face off against a tough Dolphins passing defense. Miami has allowed just 155 passing yards per game in 2024, best in the league.
outlooksByWeek.9: Marvin Harrison broke out of his recent slump in Week 8, catching six of seven targets for 111 yards and a touchdown. It was Harrison's first 100+ yard receiving game since Week 2. Harrison's playing time and opportunities are not an issue in the Arizona offense, and some of his inconsistency this season can be attributed to his high average depth of target. Harrison will look to continue his positive momentum in Week 9 when the Cardinals take on the Bears. Chicago's defense has allowed 199 passing yards per game in 2024, 11th best in the league.
outlooksByWeek.10: Marvin Harrison caught two of five targets for 35 yards in Week 9. On the one hand, Arizona spent most of last weekend in a positive game script and only had 20 passing attempts. This led to a dearth of opportunities for all of Arizona's wide receivers. On the other hand, Harrison continues to be utilized on the perimeter with deeper targets, leading to a low catch rate and boom-bust weekly outcomes in fantasy. He faces off against a strong Jets secondary in Week 10. The Jets' passing defense has allowed 158 passing yards per game this season, second best in the league.
outlooksByWeek.12: Marvin Harrison has been inconsistent on a weekly basis for the Cardinals this season. Harrison has posted a solid 22-percent target share this season, and he has played most of the team's snaps on offense. However, Arizona's 27.6 passing attempts per game are the second lowest in the league. This has resulted in solid, but not elite, target numbers for Harrison this season and likely contributes to his volatile fantasy performances. In Week 12, the Cardinals face off against the Seahawks. Seattle has had an average passing defense this season, allowing 211 yards per game.
outlooksByWeek.13: Marvin Harrison had a disappointing Week 12 outing, catching three of six targets for 47 receiving yards. Kyler Murray attempted a season-high 37 passes, though Harrison was unable to earn more opportunities on this increased passing volume. Harrison has only 3 receptions in 11 appearances this season, and he is best viewed as an inconsistent boom-or-bust option in fantasy in Week 13 when the Cardinals take on the Vikings. Minnesota has allowed 243 passing yards per game this season, fifth most in the league.
outlooksByWeek.14: Marvin Harrison caught five of 12 targets for 60 yards and a touchdown in Week 13. Before the game, coach Jonathan Gannon told the media the Cardinals intended to get the ball into Harrison's hands. While he ended up tied with Trey McBride for the most targets on the team, Harrison was fairly inefficient with his opportunities outside of his touchdown. Harrison's catch rate continues to be under 50-percent this season, and his high average depth of target has led to inconsistent fantasy performances. In Week 14, the Cardinals have a divisional game against the Seahawks. Seattle's pass defense has allowed 213 yards per game this season, which ranks 13th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.15: Marvin Harrison caught four of eight targets for 49 yards in Week 14. While Harrison continues to see a healthy amount of targets in Arizona's offense, he also continues to post a poor catch rate below 50-percent on the season. Trey McBride dominates the targets in the short and intermediate areas in this offense, while Harrison spends the majority of his snaps running deeper routes out wide. Unless his utilization in the offense changes, Harrison will likely continue to be a boom-or-bust fantasy option in Week 15 for Arizona's game against the Patriots. New England's passing defense has allowed 216 yards per game this season, which ranks 15th in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: A polished playmaker with elite NFL bloodlines, Harrison is arguably the most pro-ready player in this year's draft class, regardless of position. Kyler Murray may not be the most consistent passer in the NFL, but he has proven capable of supporting a top-15 fantasy producer at the position (DeAndre Hopkins was a top-15 WR in fantasy PPG in all three of his seasons as a Cardinal). Harrison should easily emerge as Murray's primary option, likely flirting with double-digit targets on a regular basis and making him a priority rookie in redraft and dynasty formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: Sam LaPorta, a standout rookie last season, set the new benchmark for receptions by a rookie tight end with 86 catches and added 10 touchdowns. He remains the clear second option in the Lions' passing game behind Amon-Ra St. Brown, and with room for growth in Year 2, LaPorta should continue to be a significant fantasy asset. He appears ready for Week 1 after missing part of training camp due to a hamstring issue. LaPorta has an opportunity to pick up right where he left off last season, facing a Rams defense that allowed eight touchdowns to tight ends last season, tied for 28th in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.2: Sam LaPorta had a modest performance in the season opener, catching four of five targets for 45 yards in Detroit's 26-20 overtime victory over the Rams. The tight end's impact was somewhat muted due to a less effective game from quarterback Jared Goff, though LaPorta did have an important 18-yard reception on Detroit's final drive, leading to a game-tying field goal. LaPorta will be looking to increase his involvement in Week 2 against the Buccaneers, a team he had success against in last year's postseason matchup, catching nine of 11 targets for 65 yards in the NFC Divisional Round. Although Tampa Bay limited passing yards to just 184 last week-primarily due to QB Jayden Daniels' frequent scrambles-they allowed the second-most fantasy points to TEs last season and are dealing with a number of injuries in their secondary this year.
outlooksByWeek.3: Sam LaPorta will look to rebound in Week 3 as the Lions travel to face the Cardinals. LaPorta managed just two catches for 13 yards on three targets in last week's loss to the Buccaneers, continuing a slow start to the season compared to his impressive rookie campaign. With Jameson Williams emerging as a key target, LaPorta has seen fewer opportunities, with just eight targets through two games. Despite Arizona's defense limiting tight ends to 46 yards on three catches across their first two games, their 9.0 yards per pass attempt allowed could open the door for LaPorta to find more success this week.
outlooksByWeek.4: Sam LaPorta caught both of his targets for 36 yards before exiting with a low-ankle sprain in Detroit's win over the Cardinals, casting doubt on his availability for Week 4. The sophomore tight end has averaged just 31.3 receiving yards per game and has yet to score a touchdown through three games. If LaPorta is able to suit up, he'll look to get back on track against a stingy Seahawks defense that has allowed the fewest passing yards in the NFL this season. However, Seattle did allow tight end Hunter Henry to rack up 109 yards on eight catches in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.6: Sam LaPorta could be poised for his 2024 breakout versus the Cowboys in Week 6, with the Lions coming off a bye. Though the second-year pro, who scored 10 touchdowns as a rookie, has been held out of the end zone thus far this season, he quietly logged a solid game against Seattle in Week 4, securing all four of his targets for 53 yards. Only one of those looks was in the red zone, within 20 yards, and LaPorta's only target inside the 10-yard line came Week 1. Still, LaPorta is coming off his best game of the season in terms of receiving yards, finishing second on the team in terms of both that category and receptions. Offensive coordinator Ben Johnson figures to put his early-season bye to use, so more consistency for LaPorta, and Detroit's passing production as a whole, may arrive without further delay.
outlooksByWeek.7: Sam LaPorta will look to get more involved on offense as the Lions prepare for a key Week 7 matchup against the undefeated Vikings. While LaPorta was impactful on his lone catch during the team's 47-9 blowout win over Dallas, a 52-yard touchdown that came as the result of a trick play, his consistently low target total was again disencouraging. Despite his standout rookie season, across five games in Year 2 the tight end has yet to exceed five targets in a single game, and his touchdown versus Dallas was the first of the season. In his last four appearances, LaPorta is averaging just 2.5 targets per contest. He'll hope to be more heavily leaned on during Week 7's road matchup against Minnesota, a key divisional contest that figures to be substantially more competitive than Detroit's recent affairs.
outlooksByWeek.8: Sam LaPorta's quest to get more involved on offense continues as the Lions prepare for a Week 8 home matchup against Tennessee. The second-year tight end secured one of two targets for 25 yards during Detroit's narrow divisional win over the Vikings, continuing a trend of middling volume. In fact, LaPorta has now logged back-to-back one-catch games, though he's remained impactful with those opportunities. Despite a 1-5 record, the Titans defense has found legitimate success versus opposing tight ends this season, meaning any still awaiting a potential breakout for LaPorta may have to remain patient beyond Week 8.
outlooksByWeek.9: Sam LaPorta will look to keep his momentum up as the Lions face off against the Packers in Week 9. The second-year tight end is coming off his best game of the season, having secured all six of his targets for 48 yards and a touchdown in Detroit's 52-14 win over the Titans. The Lions are averaging 43 points in their last four games, with LaPorta accounting for two touchdowns and having surpassed 40 yards three times in that span. His target total versus Tennessee was a season-high mark, and perhaps by no coincidence came with Jameson Williams sidelined for the first contest of his two-game suspension. With Williams still out versus Green Bay, LaPorta will have another clear opportunity to playing a lead role in Detroit's passing attack.
outlooksByWeek.10: Sam LaPorta will hope more opportunities come his way as the Lions travel to Houston in Week 10. Despite No. 2 wideout Jameson Williams missing the second, and final, game of his suspension Week 9 versus Green Bay, LaPorta finished with just two catches for 28 yards on three targets. Despite those uninspiring numbers, LaPorta actually finished second on the team in terms of receiving, behind just Amon-Ra St. Brown (7-56-1). That comes largely due to the combination of a positive game script and rainy conditions, which allowed Detroit to comfortably lean on the run. Williams' return versus the Texans means LaPorta's opportunities will again be cut into. The second-year TE continues what's been a middling Year 2 campaign, as he's been held to two or fewer receptions in five of eight appearances and has just two touchdowns on the year.
outlooksByWeek.11: Sam LaPorta will work to get healthy in time to contribute Week 11 for the Lions' road matchup against Jacksonville. The star tight end was forced out of Detroit's narrow primetime win over Houston due to a sprained AC joint, recording 66 yards and a touchdown before leaving the field. LaPorta's status for Week 11 against the Jaguars has to be considered up-in-the-air due to the severity of the injury. Brock Wright will have a chance to step up as the Lions' top tight end in the event that LaPorta misses any time.
outlooksByWeek.12: Sam LaPorta will work to get healthy and time to retake the field for Detroit's road week 12 matchup against Indianapolis. The second-year tight ends AC joint sprain prevented him from practicing in any capacity prior to being ruled out for Detroit's blowout win over Jacksonville. That said, head coach Dan Campbell labeled LaPorta day-to-day, an apparent indication that he has a chance to be ready Week 12. If LaPorta can't go, Brock Wright and Shane Zylstra will again split reps at the tight end position.
outlooksByWeek.13: Sam LaPorta will look to do more with his opportunities as the Lions prepare for a Thanksgiving day divisional matchup against the Bears in Week 13. In his return from a one-game absence due to a shoulder injury, LaPorta garnered an impressive six targets, the third-most on the team. He translated those into just three grabs for 19 yards, though, just the fourth time this season LaPorta has been held below 30 yards. Now another game removed from the shoulder issue, however, LaPorta could do a better job of producing in primetime versus Chicago.
outlooksByWeek.14: Sam LaPorta will continue operating as one of Jared Goff's key pass-catchers as the Lions prepare for a Thursday night divisional matchup against the Packers in Week 14. Detroit is fresh off another Thursday divisional matchup, a 23-20 win over the Bears on Thanksgiving, a game in which LaPorta secured three of six targets for just six yards, but two touchdowns. LaPorta is suffering from regression after an impressive rookie campaign, as he's now averaging 35.5 yards per game compared to 52.3 in 2023.
outlooksByWeek.15: Sam LaPorta will work to continue putting together some consistency heading into a Week 15 home matchup against the Bills. The second-year tight end was Detroit's second leading receiver during last Thursday's narrow divisional win over Green Bay, with five catches for 54 yards on seven targets. In fact, LaPorta logged his season-high target total during the 34-31 win, while his 54 receiving yards were his second-best mark of the 2024 campaign. Compared to his historic rookie season, LaPorta's production remains somewhat disappointing, but he's now demanded six or more targets in four of his last five appearances. He'll be a solid bet to produce Week 15, even against a tough Buffalo defense.

player.seasonOutlook: LaPorta is back as the Lions' starting tight end after putting together a historic rookie season which saw him finish the season as TE1. LaPorta and Jared Goff immediately hit it off, with the young tight end becoming a trusted target and ranking top five in routes, targets, receptions, receiving yards, touchdowns and end zone targets, as well as finishing second in team target share. Fantasy managers should expect more of the same in 2024 with the Lions returning the majority of their starting offense, LaPorta should be the top tight end off the board on draft day.

outlooksByWeek.1: Xavier Worthy set a Combine record by posting a time of 4.21 seconds in the 40-yard dash, and that performance, along with his strong college production, caused Kansas City to nab him with the 28th overall pick in the 2024 Draft. Tyreek Hill comparisons are inevitable given the team he ended up with, and Worthy could prove to be a similarly dangerous deep threat while hauling in passes from Patrick Mahomes behind overmatched cornerbacks. The Texas product has a lot to prove against NFL defenders given his tiny frame, but his aptitude on bubble screens fits nicely into Andy Reid's offensive scheme. His main competition for deep targets, Marquise Brown, is also dealing with a shoulder injury to begin the season, putting Worthy in position to make an immediate impact in Week 1 even against a stingy Ravens secondary that led the league in 2023 by allowing just 6.20 yards per target to wideouts.
outlooksByWeek.2: Xavier Worthy had an immediate presence in his NFL debut last week, scoring two touchdowns with 68 scrimmage yards on only three touches. The 28th overall pick in the 2024 Draft, Worthy's elite speed was on full display when he maneuvered through the Ravens defense on an end-around in the first quarter for Kansas City's first points of the season. The rookie wideout was well behind running back Isiah Pacheco and top receiver Rashee Rice in touch volume, but his ability to produce a chunk play at any time should encourage Patrick Mahomes to get the ball in his hands more often. Worthy will look for the end zone again in Week 2 against a Bengals defense that looked very vulnerable on the ground in its opener and wasn't tested at all through the air.
outlooksByWeek.3: Xavier Worthy wasn't able to build on a dynamic NFL debut in Kansas City's opener, managing only 22 scrimmage yards on three touches in Week 2's win over the Bengals. The rookie speedster's low touch volume is a little concerning, but he could be more involved over the coming weeks with running back Isiah Pacheco sidelined by a fractured fibula. The defending Super Bowl champions will need someone other than Rashee Rice to step up as a consistent option, and Worthy is a candidate to break off a big gain every time he gets the ball in his hands. He'll face a Falcons defense in Week 3 that ranks in the top 10 in fewest receiving yards allowed to WRs through two weeks.
outlooksByWeek.4: Xavier Worthy has yet to come close to matching his dazzling NFL debut, turning eight touches into only 52 scrimmage yards and zero touchdowns over the last two games. Andy Reid is making it a point to get the ball in the hands of the rookie speedster, but he hasn't been able to break away for any big gains since scoring twice in Week 1. The Kansas City offense is still searching for playmakers aside from Rashee Rice, so Worthy should continue to get opportunities, and his role should grow if he begins to capitalize on them more often. That seems unlikely to happen in Week 4 against a Chargers' secondary that's tied for fifth in the league in receptions allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.5: Xavier Worthy is coming of a strong performance in Week 4, catching three of four targets for a career-high 73 yards and his third touchdown in four games. The rookie wideout didn't gather increased volume in the contest even after Rashee Rice made an early exit for Kansas City, but that seems likely to change with Rice feared lost for the season with an ACL tear. With Hollywood Brown already on IR due to shoulder surgery, Patrick Mahomes seemingly has only Travis Kelce and Worthy left as dangerous downfield options, although JuJu Smith-Schuster, Justin Watson, Mecole Hardman and Skyy Moore should also get opportunities to step up. Worthy will look to turn his speed into production again in Week 5 against a Saints secondary that ranks in the bottom seven in the league in catches and receiving yards allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.7: Xavier Worthy scored four touchdowns in his first five NFL games before Kansas City's Week 6 bye, two through the air and two on the ground, but he's topped 30 scrimmage yards only twice in that time. The rookie speedster has a golden opportunity to develop into Patrick Mahomes' top downfield option however, with Rashee Rice and Hollywood Brown both lost for the season. Worthy's main competition for the role is veteran JuJu Smith-Schuster, with tight end Travis Kelce still able to keep the chains moving and do damage underneath. Worthy will look to top his career-high six targets in Week 7 against a 49ers secondary that's been vulnerable to big plays this season, ranking 22nd in yards per completion allowed.
outlooksByWeek.8: Xavier Worthy registered a career-high eight targets in Week 7 and added one carry, but he turned that volume into just 24 scrimmage yards. The rookie speedster's role in the Kansas City offense is still on the rise with Rashee Rice and Hollywood Brown both lost for the season, and JuJu Smith-Schuster also dealing with a hamstring injury. Worthy is capable of taking any touch to the house, but until he shows more chemistry with Patrick Mahomes, he'll be a volatile fantasy option. Worthy's Week 8 matchup against the Raiders looks tough on paper, but the Las Vegas secondary hasn't been challenged much in recent weeks due to the weakness of the team's run defense, and it did get burned by Zay Flowers (7-91-1) and Diontae Johnson (8-122-1) earlier in the year.
outlooksByWeek.9: Xavier Worthy has made a big difference with little volume to begin his NFL career. The rookie speedster scored his fifth touchdown of the season (three through the air, two on the ground) in Kansas City's Week 8 win over the Raiders, despite only registering only 26 touches through seven games. Worthy's role in the offense is growing, as he's logged eight targets in each of the last two games, but that hasn't yet translated into consistent yardage. He remains a big-play candidate with a shaky floor in Week 9 against a Buccaneers secondary that ranks in the bottom six in catches and receiving yards allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.10: Xavier Worthy couldn't gain any traction in Week 9, failing to catch either of his two targets and losing 10 yards on his two carries. The rookie speedster has had trouble carving out regular usage in the Kansas City offense, and with DeAndre Hopkins seemingly locked into the No. 1 WR role, Worthy's production could be erratic in the second half. The return of JuJu Smith-Schuster from a hamstring strain could also limit Worthy's volume further. In Week 10, he'll face a Broncos secondary that ranks in the middle of the pack in catches and receiving yards allowed to wideouts.
outlooksByWeek.11: Xavier Worthy has failed to take advantage of increased opportunities in the wake of Rashee Rice's season-ending knee injury. Over four games since Kansas City's Week 6 bye, Worthy has collected 22 targets but caught only eight of them for 67 yards and a touchdown. The rookie speedster still has game-breaking potential when he gets the ball in his hands, but without better chemistry with Patrick Mahomes, he's a volatile fantasy play at best. Worthy will face a Bills secondary in Week 11 that ranks in the top 12 in the league in receiving yards and touchdowns allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.12: Xavier Worthy racked up 68 scrimmage yards and a touchdown on only five touches in Week 11, his best performance since Week 4. The 2024 first-round pick has had a bumpy rookie season, but Kansas City coach Andy Reid promised last week to get the speedster more involved, and he was true to his word. Worthy has six TDs on only 34 touches over his first 10 NFL games, and he could be a big asset for the defending Super Bowl champions down the stretch. Worthy might contribute again in Week 12 against a Panthers secondary that's been vulnerable to big plays and sits 29th in TD% allowed, giving up 18 passing touchdowns on only 307 attempts.
outlooksByWeek.13: Xavier has yet to catch more than four passes in a contest, and over six games since the Chief's bye he's managed a 16-174-2 line on 33 targets. Coach Andy Reid has publicly committed to getting the speedster more involved, but as yet Worthy hasn't established real chemistry with Patrick Mahomes, limiting his upside. Worthy will try to take a step forward in Week 13 against a Raiders secondary that ranks eighth in the league in receiving yards allowed to WRs, although it has been more vulnerable through the air of late.
outlooksByWeek.14: Xavier Worthy's role continues to grow in the Kansas City offense. The rookie has caught at least four passes in three straight games, posting a 13-161-1 line on 18 targets over that stretch. While veteran DeAndre Hopkins appears to have solidified his spot as the team's top wideout, and Patrick Mahomes is very comfortable feeding his tight ends, Worthy's elite speed is becoming a more important part of Andy Reid's game plan as the playoffs approach. Worthy will look for a breakout performance in Week 14 against a Chargers secondary that ranks ninth in the league in receptions allowed to wideouts.
outlooksByWeek.15: Xavier Worthy appears to have found a consistent role in the Kansas City passing game. The rookie speedster has caught at least four passes in four straight games, posting an 18-202-1 line on 24 targets over that stretch while also getting occasional carries on jet sweeps as well. Worthy has settled in as the team's No. 2 wideout, but that role could be threatened if Hollywood Brown comes off IR before the end of the regular season. Worthy will take on a Browns defense in Week 15 that has been vulnerable to big plays, ranking 25th in receiving yards allowed to WRs despite being tied for second in catches allowed to the position.

player.seasonOutlook: That the Chiefs paid handsomely to move up to 28th overall in the NFL draft to select Worthy speaks volumes about their regard for his big-play ability. In his final season at Texas, he averaged 7.7 yards after the catch per target and broke 15 tackles, and he ultimately broke the 40-yard dash record at the NFL combine (4.21 seconds). Though the Chiefs' receiving depth should afford them patience with Worthy's development, his ability to stretch the field will prove handy to them from Day 1. If he clicks, he could deliver fantasy WR3 numbers right from the start. Bear in mind, however, that players of his ilk often have their single-game statistical peaks and valleys.

While not as staunch as in previous years, the 49ers D/ST remained a formidable unit in 2023, tallying 48 sacks, 22 INTs and allowing the fourth-fewest completions of 40+ yards (five). San Francisco's defensive line experienced a good amount of turnover this offseason, losing Arik Armstead, Chase Young and Javon Kinlaw, while adding Leonard Floyd, Yetur Gross-Matos and Maliek Collins. The team also addressed the secondary via the draft, adding DBs in the second and fourth rounds. As such, San Francisco figures to remain a top-five D/ST, flirting with double-digit fantasy points on a weekly basis.

outlooksByWeek.1: Courtland Sutton emerged as a favorite red-zone target for Russell Wilson in 2023, scoring eight of his career-high 10 receiving touchdowns from inside the 20, but the rest of his production in a sluggish Broncos passing game was a disappointment. Wilson is now in Pittsburgh, but Jerry Jeudy is also gone, leaving Sutton as the clear top wideout on the Denver roster. If he establishes chemistry with rookie quarterback Bo Nix quickly, Sutton could reach 1,000 yards for the first time since 2019.  In Week 1, he'll take on a Seahawks secondary that ranked in the bottom half of the league in 2023 in receiving yards and yards per target allowed to wide receivers.
outlooksByWeek.2: Courtland Sutton failed to produce much offense in the Broncos' Week 1 loss to the Seahawks, but there were some encouraging signs. The wideout led the team in targets with 12 as QB Bo Nix looked his way often, but the duo couldn't get on the same page and that volume left Sutton with only four catches for 38 yards. While it's encouraging that Sutton is the clear top downfield option for Nix, his upside will be limited while the rookie is getting acclimated to the NFL. Denver's schedule doesn't get any easier in Week 2 as the team faces a Pittsburgh defense that shut down Atlanta's more talented offense in its opener.
outlooksByWeek.3: Courtland Sutton failed to make a difference in Week 2's loss to the Steelers, catching just one of his four targets for 26 yards. It was a steep drop in volume, but not efficiency, for the veteran wideout, who collected 12 targets in the Broncos' opener but only managed four receptions for 38 yards. He's had trouble getting on the same page as rookie quarterback Bo Nix, but secondaries have also keyed on Sutton as the only downfield option they have, with young receivers Marvin Mims and Troy Franklin all but invisible. Sutton could be in for another high-volume day in Week 3 against a Buccaneers defense allowing the sixth most receptions to WRs through two weeks but has yet to give up a passing score.
outlooksByWeek.4: Courtland Sutton notched double-digit targets in Week 3 for the second time in three games this season, but for the first time he turned the volume into decent production, catching seven of 11 targets for 68 yards. Improved play from Broncos rookie quarterback Bo Nix helped spur the boost, but Sutton's spot atop the wideout pecking order remains unchallenged. The fifth-year player has 27 targets on the year, while Josh Reynolds is a distant second on Denver with 15. Sutton faces a tough test in Week 4 against a Jets secondary that sits seventh in the league in receiving yards allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.5: Courtland Sutton is coming off a statistically improbable performance, amassing 60 receiving yards in Week 4 despite the fact that quarterback Bo Nix only managed 60 total passing yards. Sutton also scored his first touchdown of the season, and while the Broncos' passing game continues to struggle, the veteran wideout is locked into the top spot. Through four games, he has 36 targets, accounting for 26.1% of Nix's pass attempts. Sutton will look to turn his steady volume into bigger production in Week 5 against a Raiders secondary that sits in the bottom half of the league in catches, receiving yards and receiving touchdowns allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.6: Courtland Sutton continues to garner inconsistent volume in the Broncos' sputtering passing game. The veteran wideout managed only two catches for 32 yards on five targets in Week 5 after collecting 20 targets over the prior two games combined. Rookie quarterback Bo Nix is showing signs of progress, but he isn't yet at the point that any of his pass-catching options can be considered reliable assets. Sutton will face a Chargers defense in Week 6 that has allowed the fewest receptions per game in the league to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.7: Courtland Sutton scored a spectacular one-handed touchdown in Week 6 against the Chargers, salvaging an otherwise lackluster performance that saw him haul in four of six targets for 53 yards. While the veteran remains the Broncos' top wideout, rookie QB Bo Nix is still a work in progress and hasn't yet shown he can stretch the field consistently, limiting the upside of all the team's receiving options, including Sutton. The Denver passing game could break out in Week 7 against a Saints secondary that just got torched by Baker Mayfield, leading to an 11-125-2 line for Chris Godwin, putting Sutton in the fantasy mix.
outlooksByWeek.8: Courtland Sutton posted a stunning goose egg in a Week 7 rout of the Saints, failing to even get a target. Rookie quarterback Bo Nix attempted 26 passes, but he instead focused on younger options like rookie wideout Troy Franklin. Sutton remains at the top of the WR depth chart for the Broncos, but he hasn't seen double-digit targets since Week 3 and hasn't topped 68 receiving yards all year, giving him a limited ceiling in the team's low-wattage offense. Sutton may not get many chances to rebound in Week 8 against a Panthers defense that's been more vulnerable on the ground than through the air, but which still ranks near the bottom of the league in passing yards per game allowed and passing TDs allowed.
outlooksByWeek.9: Courtland Sutton broke out in Week 8, setting season highs with eight catches for 100 yards while logging double-digit targets for the first time since Week 3. The Broncos' top wideout is beginning to develop chemistry with rookie QB Bo Nix, although Sutton's big performance against the Panthers came just one week after he went without a target against the Saints. That disappearing act has been the exception, as he's posted a 17-245-2 line in total over the last five contests. Sutton could be poised for big numbers again in Week 9 against a Ravens secondary that's coughed up the most receiving yards and most touchdowns in the league to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.10: Courtland Sutton endured a shaky start to the season, but he's found some chemistry with Broncos rookie quarterback Bo Nix over the last two weeks. Sutton has reached 100 receiving yards in each contest, posting a 15-222-0 line on 21 targets and even throwing a TD pass of his own to Nix in Week 9 against the Ravens. The wideout is the clear top downfield option for Denver, and Sutton's 499 receiving yards on the year is more than double that of his closest teammate, running back Javonte Williams. Sutton's hot streak could come to an abrupt halt in Week 10 against a Kansas City secondary that's given up the fewest receiving yards in the league to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.11: Courtland Sutton has taken full advantage of rookie quarterback Bo Nix's increasing comfort level with the Broncos' offense. Between Weeks 8 and 10, Sutton amassed a 21-292-1 line on 30 targets, accounting for 40.4% of Nix's passing yards over that stretch. The veteran wideout's surge has him almost on pace for his second career 1,000-yard campaign, a mark he hasn't reached since 2019. Sutton figures to be productive again in Week 11 against a Falcons secondary that ranks in the bottom five in receptions and receiving touchdowns allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.12: Courtland Sutton continues to shine as the top downfield option for rookie quarterback Bo Nix. Over the last four games, Sutton has put together a 28-370-1 line on 38 targets while hauling in at least 70 yards in each contest. Nix is on the rise, and the Broncos have a mostly favorable schedule to close out the season, which should help ensure Sutton maintains heavy target volume. He faces a tough matchup in Week 12 however, against a Raiders defense that's been more vulnerable on the ground, and which ranks third in the league in fewest receiving yards allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.13: Courtland Sutton is coming off his first two-touchdown game of the season in a Week 12 win over the Raiders. The veteran wideout has produced elite numbers over the last five games, compiling a 36-467-3 line on 48 targets as Bo Nix's clear No. 1 option. The Broncos don't have any other skill-position players that seem capable of making a consistent contribution, which should keep Sutton very busy down the stretch. In Week 13 he'll face a Browns secondary that's been vulnerable to big plays this year, as the unit is tied for fourth in catches allowed to WRs but is in the bottom 10 in receiving yards and TDs allowed to the position.
outlooksByWeek.15: Courtland Sutton continues to dominate looks from rookie quarterback Bo Nix as the Broncos' No. 1 wide receiver. Sutton hasn't gotten fewer than eight targets in six straight games, posting a 42-569-3 line on 57 targets over that stretch. He's also topped 100 receiving yards in three of those contests, after failing to reach triple digits in the first seven weeks of the season. Sutton will look to keep rolling in Week 15 against a Colts secondary that ranks 21st in receptions allowed to WRs.

player.seasonOutlook: Following along with what was a team-wide theme, Sutton fell short of expectations again in 2023, marking three consecutive seasons he has failed to crack the positional top 30 in fantasy points despite pacing the Broncos in both routes run and targets. Though his career-best 10 touchdowns were a bright spot, advanced measures deemed it a fortunate total. And since he entered the season with just 14 TDs in 65 career games, it was quite a surprise. Sutton enters his age-29 season working with his ninth different quarterback, and one probably a step down talent-wise from Russell Wilson. Still, the offseason trade of Jerry Jeudy opens up some targets and paves the way for Sutton to be the Broncos' receiving alpha dog. He's best drafted as a WR3 with potential receptions upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: DeAndre Hopkins is recovering from a knee injury, but he's on track to suit up in Week 1 against a Bears defense that allowed the sixth-most touchdowns to wide receivers in 2023 but limited the position to the ninth-fewest receiving yards. The 32-year-old wide receiver got off to a slow start last season but enjoyed a resurgence after the Titans inserted Will Levis under center in Week 8, as all seven of Hopkins' touchdowns came from that point onward, and six of them were thrown by Levis. Offseason WR additions Calvin Ridley and Tyler Boyd will likely cut into Hopkins' target share, but they will also draw attention from a Bears secondary that brought back its top three cornerbacks from 2023, including Jaylon Johnson.
outlooksByWeek.2: DeAndre Hopkins was limited to just eight yards in Week 1 while playing through a knee injury, and he may still be hampered by the injury in Week 2 against the elite Jets secondary. Standout cornerbacks Sauce Gardner and DJ Reed are back in green and white for 2024 after helping the Jets limit wide receivers to the fewest yards in the NFL last season. Hopkins has accounted for six of Will Levis' nine career touchdown passes through the second-year QB's first 10 NFL starts, but Levis threw for just 127 yards in the season opener, and his struggles may continue to hold back Tennessee's entire passing game.
outlooksByWeek.3: DeAndre Hopkins had just one catch in each of the Titans' first two games, but he will look to ramp up his involvement in Week 3 against the Packers as he gets further removed from his knee injury. The veteran WR's Week 1 availability came down to the wire, but Hopkins avoided a Week 2 injury designation, and he should be even closer to 100 percent for Week 3. Calvin Ridley has supplanted Hopkins as the top target for QB Will Levis, but there should be enough success to go around for both wideouts against a Packers secondary that's allowing 161.5 yards per game to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.4: DeAndre Hopkins showed that he's healthy again with 73 yards and a TD in Week 3 after mustering only 17 yards through two games as he worked his way back from a knee injury. The Titans have a balanced receiving corps with Hopkins' physicality complemented by Calvin Ridley's speed on the outside and Tyler Boyd's precise route running in the slot, but each of those three players has only eight catches heading into a Week 4 road game against Miami's middling secondary. With QB Will Levis struggling, it will be hard to trust Hopkins as anything more than a flex play in Week 4, though at least Hopkins is responsible for seven of Levis' 12 career touchdown passes.
outlooksByWeek.6: DeAndre Hopkins has caught seven of Will Levis' 12 career touchdown passes, and the duo would have an excellent opportunity to add to that connection in Week 6 against the Colts if Levis is able to play through a shoulder injury. Should the big-armed Levis sit, it would lower the ceiling for Tennessee's entire passing game considering backup Mason Rudolph threw for only 85 yards in more than three quarters after replacing the injured Rudolph in Tennessee's 31-12 Week 4 win over Miami. The Colts have allowed the fourth-most yards per game to WRs, so Hopkins will have fantasy appeal regardless of Tennessee's QB situation, though he profiles as a WR2 with Levis or a WR3 with Rudolph.
outlooksByWeek.7: DeAndre Hopkins had a team-high 54 receiving yards in Tennessee's Week 6 loss to the Colts, marking the third consecutive game in which he had at least a share of the team lead in receiving yards. The Titans passing game will be fighting an uphill battle in Week 7 against a Bills secondary that has allowed only eight passing TDs, but Hopkins looks like the team's second-best Week 7 fantasy play after RB Tony Pollard. Hopkins' strong contested catch ability makes him a solid flex play against a Buffalo cornerback corps that doesn't allow much separation.
outlooksByWeek.8: DeAndre Hopkins was traded to Kansas City on Wednesday from Tennessee, and he'll likely make his Chiefs debut in Week 8 against the Raiders. Hopkins gets a massive upgrade in quarterback play from Will Levis (shoulder) and Mason Rudolph to Patrick Mahomes, and the veteran WR is likely to climb to the top of the depth chart before long since Rashee Rice (knee) and Marquise Brown (shoulder) are out for the season and JuJu Smith-Schuster (hamstring) has already been ruled out for Week 8. The Raiders have been stingier than league average against WRs.
outlooksByWeek.9: DeAndre Hopkins failed to make much of a contribution in his Kansas City debut, catching two of three targets for 29 yards in a Week 8 win over the Raiders. The veteran played only 22 snaps as he gets up to speed on the playbook, and he should be able to quickly take over the WR1 role that was vacated when Rashee Rice went down with a season-ending knee injury. Hopkins had four catches of 40-plus yards last season with the Titans, and he should be able to supply a big-play source once he and Patrick Mahomes develop some chemistry. Hopkins could break out in Week 9 against a Buccaneers secondary that ranks in the bottom six in catches and receiving yards allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.10: DeAndre Hopkins had a breakout performance in his second game with Kansas City, hauling in two touchdowns passes in Week 9 against the Buccaneers. The veteran wideout also set season highs with eight catches for 86 yards on nine targets, and he's quickly cemented his spot at Patrick Mahomes' top downfield option. Hopkins posted his seventh career 1,000-yard campaign in 2023 with the Titans, and the 32-year-old still seems capable of putting together a huge second half with the defending Super Bowl champions.  Hopkins could be shadowed by Patrick Surtain in Week 10, but overall this season the Broncos' secondary ranks in the middle of the pack in catches and receiving yards allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.11: DeAndre Hopkins continues to adjust to his new scheme and new quarterback. In three games since being acquired by Kansas City, the veteran wideout has delivered a 14-171-2 line on 17 targets, but most of that production came in Week 9 against the Buccaneers. Hopkins appears to be the WR1 for Patrick Mahomes, but he has yet to see big volume in that role as Travis Kelce and others have a more established rapport with the QB. Hopkins will face a Bills secondary in Week 11 that ranks in the top 12 in the league in receiving yards and touchdowns allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.12: DeAndre Hopkins is coming off another quiet performance in Week 11, catching three of four targets for 29 yards. The addition of the veteran receiver has raised the ceiling of the Kansas City passing attack, but Hopkins himself hasn't particularly benefitted, managing only one big game in four appearances for his new club. As his rapport with Patrick Mahomes develops, stronger performances could be ahead. Hopkins could pop in Week 12 against a Panthers secondary that's been vulnerable to big plays and sits 29th in TD% allowed, giving up 18 passing touchdowns on only 307 attempts.
outlooksByWeek.13: DeAndre Hopkins found the end zone in Week 12 against the Panthers, his third touchdown in five games since being traded to Kansas City. The veteran wideout has topped six targets only once during that stretch, and while he seems to have earned Patrick Mahomes' trust in the red zone, his 235 receiving yards on 22 catches for his new team is underwhelming. Hopkins also has plenty of competition for those high-value targets, as Travis Kelce, rookie Xavier Worthy and even backup tight end Noah Gray have put together big performances in recent weeks. Hopkins will try to take his turn in Week 13 against a Raiders secondary that got torched by Courtland Sutton in its last game.
outlooksByWeek.14: DeAndre Hopkins is coming off one of his most productive performances since being traded to Kansas City. His nine targets in Week 13 tied his season high, while his 90 receiving yards set a new season high. Hopkin failed to reach 60 yards in four of six games since being paired with Patrick Mahomes, so the two may not have consistent chemistry quite yet. Hopkins will look to build on that effort in Week 14 against a Chargers secondary that ranks ninth in the league in receptions allowed to wideouts.
outlooksByWeek.15: DeAndre Hopkins found the end zone in Week 14, his fourth touchdown in seven games since being acquired by Kansas City. The veteran wideout has gotten nine targets in back-to-back contests, but he's turned them into just eight catches for 132 yards as the team's passing game continues to tread water. Hopkins' target volume is at least intriguing and he appears to be Patrick Mahomes' top option, but that role hasn't led to consistent production. Hopkins will try to break out in Week 15 against a Browns secondary that has given up plenty of big plays, ranking 25th in receiving yards allowed to WRs despite being tied for second in catches allowed to the position.

player.seasonOutlook: Hopkins is entering his 12th NFL season, but he hasn't shown serious signs of aging just yet. Last season, Hopkins posted his highest yards per catch since his first All-Pro effort in 2017. The days of triple-digit reception totals are likely in the past, but a concentrated Titans offense could still afford him well over 100 targets working with a big-armed second-year QB in Will Levis. There is always a degree of risk investing in a receiver in his age-32 season, although it's reasonable to note Hopkins wins at the catch point with a mixture of guile and hands that remains rare at the position. Given the track record, don't be surprised by another solid WR2 showing found at WR3 pricing, though note that Hopkins is expected to miss the first few games of the season due to injury.

outlooksByWeek.1: Amari Cooper will kick off the 2024 season with a Week 1 matchup against his former team, the Dallas Cowboys. He has 128 and 132 targets in his two seasons with the Browns, respectively, and should remain the primary target of quarterback Deshaun Watson once again. That doesn't guarantee immediate success, however, as Cooper faces a tough Dallas secondary that allowed the seventh-fewest fantasy points per game to opposing wide receivers in 2023 and also welcomes back Trevon Diggs. Nevertheless, Cooper has a locked-in role and has topped 1,000 receiving yards in four of his last five seasons.
outlooksByWeek.2: Amari Cooper struggled in Week 1 against Dallas, like the entire Cleveland offense. He did register an encouraging nine targets to lead the team and narrowly missed out on a long touchdown. The matchup should also be on his side in Week 2 against Jacksonville, who lack the same playmakers that Dallas has on the defensive side of the ball. Cooper is a risky option due to poor quarterback play for the Browns, but he should be at the center of the team's passing game.
outlooksByWeek.3: Amari Cooper has seen excellent opportunity through two weeks for Cleveland, racking up a combined 17 targets. However, he's lacked rapport with Deshaun Watson, as he's recorded only five receptions for 27 yards -- good for an abysmal 1.6 yards per target. While there is long-term concern regarding Watson's ability to lead an effective offense, there is also reason to believe that Cooper will produce better stats due to his lengthy track record of success. That could begin in a Week 3 matchup against the Giants, as their secondary was exploited by the Vikings in Week 1 and is generally inexperienced.
outlooksByWeek.4: Amari Cooper has had plenty of opportunity to produce in the Cleveland offense to start the season, commanding 29 targets through three games. He finally delivered a strong stat line in Week 3, and his inconsistent results highlight the poor quarterback play of Deshaun Watson and the state of the offense in general. There's risk involved, but Cooper should be a safe bet to lead the team in targets in a Week 4 matchup against the Raiders, who have allowed both Zay Flowers and Diontae Johnson to top 90 receiving yards and a touchdown in consecutive weeks.
outlooksByWeek.5: Amari Cooper has at least eight targets in all four games this season and is Deshaun Watson's favorite target in the Cleveland offense. That's led to mostly poor results, as he has under 40 receiving yards in three contests, though it is worth noting that Cooper had an 82-yard touchdown catch wiped off the board by a questionable penalty late in the fourth quarter in Week 4 against the Raiders. A Week 5 matchup against the Commanders should set Cooper up for a successful week, with the Washington defense allowing the most points per game to opposing wide receivers this season. Cooper is viable as a WR2 based on his volume and the defense he is facing.
outlooksByWeek.6: Amari Cooper continues to command prolific volume in the Cleveland offense, as he has yet to register fewer than eight targets in a game this season. However, dismal quarterback play has hurt his ability to translate opportunity into production, as he's averaged only 10.4 yards per reception while hauling in just 42.6% of his targets. Cooper's opportunity alone should keep him in consideration for fantasy lineups, and that's particularly true in a Week 6 matchup against an Eagles defense that has allowed the fifth-most fantasy points per game to opposing wide receivers. The floor is non-existent, but Cooper is a WR3 with the chance to do better.
outlooksByWeek.7: Amari Cooper has been among the most frustrating fantasy options, but a trade to the Bills should flip the script. There could be an acclimation period with QB Josh Allen, but Cooper will be the club's No. 1 WR in short order. Assuming Cooper makes his Bills debut in Week 7, he's a fantasy starter despite facing a Titans defense allowing only 151.2 passing yards per game, while surrendering just two scoring strikes.
outlooksByWeek.8: Making his Bills debut after a mid-week trade, Amari Cooper posted four catches on five targets for 66 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 despite just a 33% snap share. With a full week of reps and playbook familiarity ahead, Cooper is poised for an even better showing in Week 8 at Seattle. The Seahawks are allowing a middling 7.0 yards per reception through seven games, but they've surrendered 17 catches of 20-plus yards and four of 40-plus yards, the third-highest total in the league, giving Cooper a volume floor and big play ceiling with WR1 potential.
outlooksByWeek.9: Amari Cooper is still finding his footing as he enters his third week as a member of the Bills. He drew five targets on a limited 33% snap share in his Week 7, but that fell to a three-yard catch on two looks in Week 8 despite nearly doubling his snap count. Better days are coming, perhaps as soon as Week 9 where a potential high-scoring affair against the Dolphins looms. Cooper should be more involved, but Buffalo is spreading the wealth across their passing game, landing Cooper in WR2 territory.
outlooksByWeek.10: Amari Cooper has failed to make a significant difference since the Bills acquired him three weeks ago, garnering just seven targets, resulting in five catches and 69 yards while not playing in Week 9 due to a wrist injury. His mere presence has opened up the team's passing game, and his unavailability came as a surprise, so it's reasonable to expect he returns in Week 10. The matchup against a Colts defense that's been vulnerable to outside receivers and is allowing 250.6 yards per game offers immense potential, but having shown no immediate chemistry with Josh Allen, tempered expectations are prudent over a slate breaking performance.
outlooksByWeek.11: Amari Cooper has missed Weeks 9 and 10 due to a wrist injury, and the Bills have a bye after Week 11, complicating the likelihood he'll return Week 13. Cooper hasn't gained any traction since coming over from Cleveland, having only five catches, 69 yards and a touchdown on seven targets. Should he be available against Kansas City, managers have no choice but to play him despite a lack of proven chemistry with Josh Allen in a spotlight game against a Chiefs defense that's allowed 13 touchdown passes in nine games, but it should be viewed as a WR3 scenario rather than a dominating opportunity.
