outlooksByWeek.13: Health has prevented Amari Cooper from getting on track with the Bills, producing just seven catches for 124 yards and a touchdown in three games. Coming out of a bye, managers will need to monitor Cooper's wrist and whether he's able to shed a cast he played with in Week 11. The upside with QB Josh Allen remains immense, but Week 13 offers a challenging matchup against a 49ers secondary that's allowing just 205.8 yards per game, best suiting fantasy managers to view Cooper as a WR3 with touchdown potential.
outlooksByWeek.14: Amari Cooper has yet to pop in a Bills uniform, logging just 13 targets over the last four games, accounting for 10 catches, 136 yards and a touchdown. His Week 13 outing (three catches, 12 yards) can be written off due to snow and a heavy run-based game plan, but his overall offensive involvement can't inspire confidence. A Week 14 matchup with the Rams does however, as their secondary is allowing 7.9 yards per attempt, the fourth-highest total in the league, allowing Cooper to safely slot in as a WR3 with the potential for more.
outlooksByWeek.15: After recording just 13 targets in the Bills last four games, Amari Cooper erupted for 14 looks in Week 14, finishing with six catches and 95 yards. The long-awaited breakout for Cooper finally arrived, giving him momentum entering Week 15. The Bills travel to face a Lions defense Sunday that's statistically sound against the pass, allowing just 11 touchdown receptions in 13 games and 6.9 yards per attempt, but with points likely coming freely in a game with the slate's highest expected point total, Cooper profiles as a WR3 with the room for more.

player.seasonOutlook: Cooper is entering his 11th pro season, and third with the Browns. One of the top route technicians in the league, Cooper averaged 14.5 PPG last season (WR16), highlighted by his 51.5-point performance in Week 16 versus the Texans. Cooper has now seen 100 or more targets in five straight seasons, with at least 68 receptions each year during that stretch. The Browns traded for wide receiver Jerry Jeudy, but Cooper will remain the top target in Cleveland's schemed pass game. You can draft Cooper as a reliable flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chris Boswell enters his 10th season as Pittsburgh's kicker and remains one of the steadiest performers at the position heading into a Week 1 matchup against Atlanta. He has made at least 90 percent of his field goals in four of the last five seasons. Boswell occasionally struggles from 40 yards out and further but has missed only two of his 43 kicks inside that range combined across the last three campaigns. He'll draw a dome matchup against Atlanta in Week 1, only brightening his outlook to begin 2024.
outlooksByWeek.3: Chris Boswell has been excellent for the Steelers early on this season. He has gone 8-for-8 on three-pointers through two games, including 4-for-4 on attempts from more than 50 yards. Those efforts have come in a dome and at high altitude, both advantageous situations for kickers. Heading into a Week 3 home matchup against the Chargers, Boswell will face a stiffer test but is still a reliable fantasy option.
outlooksByWeek.4: Chris Boswell's accuracy and ability to kick from distance lands him among the every week options at the position. He lines up for another productive outing in Week 4 against the Colts.
outlooksByWeek.5: Chris Boswell has yet to miss a kick this season for the Steelers and was limited to only one field-goal attempt for the first time this season in Week 4. He should have the chance to bounce back in a Week 5 matchup against the Cowboys in what could be a fairly prolific game from an offensive perspective. Boswell isn't quite in the elite tier of kickers, but he's a solid starting option.
outlooksByWeek.6: Chris Boswell has made 12 of his 13 field-goal attempts for the Steelers this season, though he has only one field-goal attempt in Wee 4 and Week 5. A Week 6 matchup against the Raiders could provide a bounce back opportunity for as Las Vegas has allowed the fifth-most field goal attempts to opponents this season. Overall, Boswell should be considered as a starting option due to his accuracy, but he does carry risk due to Pittsburgh's conservative and often ineffective offense.
outlooksByWeek.7: Chris Boswell remains one of the most accurate kickers in the league, as he's converted 94% of his field-goal attempts through six games for the Steelers. His volume has been less reliable, as he's made multiple field goals in four of six games while being limited to one attempt in two other contests. A Week 7 matchup against the Jets lines up well for Boswell, as they have allowed 15 field-goal attempts to opposing kickers.
outlooksByWeek.8: Chris Boswell remains one of the most accurate kickers in the league, as he's now 19-for-20 on field goal attempts for the season. His opportunity has been inconsistent, as he's attempted three field goals on four occasions but only one field goal in two contests. The Pittsburgh offense showed signs of being more efficient with Russell Wilson under center in Week 7 against the Jets, making Boswell a solid starting option in Week 8 against the Giants.
outlooksByWeek.10: Chris Boswell has had a strong intersection of opportunity and accuracy halfway through the 2024 season. He made at least three field goals in each three games heading into the Week 9 bye and missed only field-goal on 24 attempts through Pittsburgh's eight games. Boswell is a strong fantasy option in Week 10 against the Commanders and will remain so until his opportunity slows.
outlooksByWeek.11: Chris Boswell was held without a field-goal attempt for the first time this season in Week 10. He's otherwise had a stellar track record for the Steelers, both in terms of accuracy and volume. He hasn't missed a kick since Week 3, and he has converted at least three field goals in three of his last four matchups. Heading into a Week 11 divisional showdown against Baltimore, Boswell should return to a more typical level of production and is a solid start for fantasy purposes.
outlooksByWeek.12: Chris Boswell accounted for all of Pittsburgh's points with six field goals for the second time of the season in Week 11. He's made at least three field goals in four of his last five games and multiple field goals in all but three contests for the campaign. He's an elite fantasy option heading into a Week 12 matchup against the Browns.
outlooksByWeek.13: Chris Boswell missed just his second field goal of the season in Week 12, though it came from 58 yards away in both snowy and windy conditions. It will be cold in Cincinnati as the Steelers head into a Week 13 showdown with the Bengals, but Boswell has been an elite kicking option by making multiple field goals in five of his last six games. Until his opportunity slows down, he's a strong starting option.
outlooksByWeek.14: Chris Boswell has enjoyed tremendous opportunity across the second half of the season, as he's attempted at least four field goals in four of his last seven games while failing to have multiple attempts just once. He's been accurate for much of the campaign but has missed kicks in each of the last two matchups heading into a Week 14 divisional showdown with the Browns. Despite the recent inconsistency, Boswell is a strong starting option.
outlooksByWeek.15: Chris Boswell entered Week 14 having missed a field-goal attempt in consecutive games, but he rebounded with a perfect effort in Pittsburgh's win over the Browns. He's made multiple field goals in four straight contests heading into a Week 15 matchup against the Eagles and has converted 92% of his field goals for the season. Boswell is a reliable fantasy option from both a volume and accuracy perspective.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tyrone Tracy enters his rookie campaign with the New York Giants with a chance to make an instant impact.  Saquon Barkley has taken his talents to Philadelphia, leaving a massive playmaking void for the G-Men out of the backfield.  Devin Singletary is the starter, but averaged a career-low 4.2 yards per tote last season, and may not shoulder the every-down rushing load due to his lack of size.  Tracy, a converted wideout, is a physical runner who impressed in preseason.  In Week 1, Tracy will face a Vikings defense that was fairly stingy against the run in 2023, allowing just 98.7 yards per tilt on the ground, which was eighth in the league.
outlooksByWeek.2: Tyrone Tracy saw little action in his NFL debut for the Giants.  Tracy managed three touches for a total of seven scrimmage yards in the 28-6 loss to the Vikings.  Tracy and Eric Gray appear to be battling for touches behind starter Devin Singletary.  As the Giants fell behind early in this contest, they were forced to largely abandon the run, allowing for even fewer running back touches than likely expected.  In Week 2, the Giants will have a chance for better results versus a mediocre Washington run defense. The Commanders allowed 112 rushing yards in their season opener, which was 15th in the NFL, though Tracy remains firmly behind the aforementioned Singletary on the depth chart.
outlooksByWeek.3: Tyrone Tracy managed just one carry for the Giants last game.  Devin Singletary remains the undisputed No. 1 running back, and took 16 carries for 95 yards and a touchdown in the 21-18 loss to the Commanders.  Coach Brian Daboll looks poised to give the shifty, diminutive Singletary virtually every chance to touch the ball out of the backfield, leaving the rookie Tracy to merely pick up the scraps.  In Week 3, the Giants will face a Browns defense allowing 114.5 yards per tilt on the ground, which is 14th in the NFL, though Tracy is unlikely to see many touches.
outlooksByWeek.4: Tyrone Tracy is coming off the best game of his young career for the Giants, taking seven touches for 40 scrimmage yards in the win over the Browns.  Tracy remains firmly behind starter Devin Singletary on the depth chart, but appears to be slowly gaining the trust of the coaching staff.   Singletary continues to garner the majority of the running back touches for the Giants, having received double-digit carries in each of the first three outings.  Even with touches likely to be limited, Tracy has an extremely favorable matchup in Week 4 versus a Cowboys defense that has been gutted on the ground thus far in 2024.  Dallas is allowing 185.7 rushing yards per clash, while also yielding eight rushing touchdowns in just three games.  Both of those statistics are dead last in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.5: Tyrone Tracy is expected to start Week 5 at the Seahawks as Devin Singletary is doubtful to play with a groin injury. Tracy has emerged as the clear-cut No. 2 running back for the Giants behind Singletary, though, so far at least, has offered little in terms of upside and production thanks to a mediocre offense. Tracy managed 21 scrimmage yards on five touches in Week 4.  This week, though, the Giants face a Seahawks defense that has been better against the pass than the run. Seattle allows 116.3 yards per game on the ground, which is 15th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.6: Tyrone Tracy rushed for 129 yards on 18 carries in place of the injured Devin Singletary, helping vault the New York Giants to a stunning win over the Seattle Seahawks. After fellow running back Eric Gray suffered a disastrous fumble on the goal line early in the game, the rookie Tracy took over and broke off several big runs for the G-Men en route to the career day. It remains to be seen if Singletary will be able to suit up for the Week 6 clash with the Bengals, but if he cannot, Tracy would likely be called upon again to shoulder the majority of the rushing load. Cincinnati has been abysmal against the run in 2024, allowing 151.4 yards per game on the ground, which is 30th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.7: Tyrone Tracy has excelled in the absence of starting running back Devin Singletary for the New York Giants.  For the second-straight game, Tracy managed over 100 scrimmage yards.  He also found the end zone for his first NFL touchdown. While Singletary could return in Week 7 versus the Eagles, at a minimum, Tracy has earned himself more touches in the offense.  The Eagles run defense has been mediocre against the run in 2024. Philadelphia is allowing 123 rushing yards per tilt, which is 17th in the NFL. However, the Eagles have yielded just three rushing touchdowns thus far in 2024, which is tied for fifth in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.8: Tyrone Tracy saw his run as the Giants starter end last game, as Devin Singletary returned to action for the New York Giants following a two-game absence.  Neither back had much success in an ugly 28-3 loss to the Eagles, though.  Singletary rushed five times for 18 yards, while also catching his lone target for three yards out of the backfield. Meanwhile, Tracy rushed six times for 23 years, and caught three passes for nine yards.  This backfield situation has all the makings of a timeshare moving forward. The matchup in Week 8 versus the Pittsburgh Steelers is not ideal either.  Pittsburgh has one of the top run defenses in the NFL, surrendering just 81 yards per clash on the ground, which is third in the league. In addition, the Steelers have allowed just three rushing touchdowns in seven games, which is tied for second in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.9: Tyrone Tracy snatched the Giants' starting running back job from Devin Singletary, only to leave a Week 8 loss twice due to injury. The first issue involved his shoulder, though Tracy was able to return to the game. The second involved a potential concussion, which sidelined him for the remainder of the contest. Tracy had rushed 20 times for 145 yards and a touchdown despite the injury-plagued outing. Unfortunately, his status is in question for a Week 9 clash with the Commanders. Washington has been rather poor against the run in 2024, allowing 139.6 yards per tilt on the ground, which is 25th in the NFL. Washington has also yielded eight rushing touchdowns, which is tied for 18th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.10: Tyrone Tracy has received 36 carries over the last two games for the Giants, parlaying those opportunities into over 200 yards rushing in the process. Tracy has usurped veteran Devin Singletary as the lead back, though the latter still rushed for 33 yards on seven carries in the last game for the G-Men. Still, Tracy will command the most touches out of the backfield in Week 10 in an extremely favorable matchup versus a struggling Carolina defense. The Panthers have allowed the most rushing yards and rushing touchdowns in the NFL to date.
outlooksByWeek.12: Tyrone Tracy has rushed for at least 100 yards and a touchdown in two of the last three games for the Giants. Unfortunately, Tracy lost a crucial fumble before the bye which ultimately cost the Giants the game versus the Panthers. Still, Tracy is averaging 5.1 yards per carry and figures to get the majority of the workload in Week 12 versus the Bucs as the Giants look to the future. Tommy DeVito will line up under center in place of the much-maligned Daniel Jones, and New York figures to lean heavily on the running game to support Tommy Cutlets. However, the Bucs have a decent run defense, allowing 125.2 yards per tilt on the ground, which is 16th in the league. Tampa Bay has also allowed just nine rushing scores in 2024, which is tied for 13th in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.13: Tyrone Tracy gained at least 65 scrimmage yards for the sixth-time in seven contests for the Giants. Tracy rushed for 42 yards and added 28 receiving yards in the 30-7 loss to the Bucs. On the downside, Tracy lost a crucial fumble for the second-straight game, and Devin Singletary also scavenged a one-yard touchdown plunge from the rookie. Given his recent fumbling issues as well as the struggles of the New York offense regardless of who lines up under center, perhaps expectations should be tempered for Tracy in Week 13. However, he will have a juicy matchup versus a Dallas defense that has been dreadful against the run in 2024. Dallas is allowing 150.5 rushing yards per tilt, which is 31st in the NFL. In addition, Dallas has allowed 19 rushing scores, which is dead last in the league.
outlooksByWeek.14: Tyrone Tracy found the end zone last game for the Giants, but his grip on the starting running back job suddenly does not seem so tight. Tracy rushed nine times for 32 yards and a touchdown versus the Cowboys, while also catching two balls for 33 yards out of the backfield. However, teammate Devin Singletary actually received the start and compiled seven rushes for 23 yards. Tracy still has more upside, but Singletary appears to have worked his way back into the mix, at least for Week 14 versus the Saints. New Orleans is allowing 136 rushing yards per game, which is 27th in the NFL. Likewise, the Saints have allowed 15 rushing touchdowns, which is tied for 25th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.15: Tyrone Tracy has found the end zone in three of the last four games for the Giants. Tracy rushed 16 times for 45 yards and a touchdown against the Saints, while also catching five passes for 38 yards out of the backfield. However, Tracy has been held under 50 yards rushing in three-straight contests, and will likely have a difficult time finding room to roam in Week 15 versus the Ravens. Baltimore has been extremely stingy against the run in 2024, allowing just 82.7 rushing yards per clash, which is first in the league. Baltimore has also allowed only 11 rushing scores this season, which is tied for 10th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: The Giants chose Tracy in the fifth round of April's draft. He shined in his one season as a running back at Purdue after several seasons as a wide receiver in Iowa's troubling offense. Of course, the Giants signed former competent Texans/Bills veteran Devin Singletary in March, and he figures to handle the bulk of the work, but Singletary has never caught more than 40 passes or tallied 300 receiving yards in a season. Tracy may become the third-down back, but this still isn't a strong offense, so don't expect more than RB5 production.

outlooksByWeek.1: James Cook will look to pick up where he left off for the Bills in a Week 1 matchup against the Cardinals. He recorded double-digit carries in the final 10 games, leading to a 1,122-yard sophomore campaign while adding a solid 44 receptions. The downside is that Cook only ran for two touchdowns while Josh Allen got 15. While you wouldn't expect Allen to replicate that, Buffalo added Ray Davis to their backfield via the draft who offers more size and power that can be used closer to the goal line. Cook's volume should remain steady and the matchup to open the year couldn't be softer as Arizona gave up the most rushing yards in the league in 2023 and didn't substantially upgrade defensively. We just need to see more scoring chances for Cook for him to take off.
outlooksByWeek.2: James Cook will look to remain the Bills focal point in a Week 2 matchup with the Dolphins on Thursday night. Somewhat surprisingly, Cook played just 60% of his team's offensive plays in the opener but turned 35 snaps into 22 touches and 103 yards. Not finding paydirt stings, and that's not going away with Josh Allen continuing to run for scores at an unprecedented rate. Cook's 3.7 YPC isn't elite, but the volume, total yards and being tied for second on the team in targets yields one of the safest roles in the league. Miami allowed 4.9 YPC in Week 1. It was their first outing without now Raider DT Christian Wilkins, rendering the 2.6 YPC Cook averaged against the Dolphins last year less concerning.
outlooksByWeek.3: James Cook has a challenging Week 3 matchup for the Bills when they face the Jaguars on Monday night. Buffalo continues to emphasize the run, with Cook recording 7.1 rushing yards per attempt in Week 2. However, the Jaguars' run defense is stout, allowing a mere 3.8 yards per carry and 103.0 yards per game. Buffalo won't abandon the run, and thus far Cook has limited involvement in the passing game with four targets in two contests. Cook is clearly a must start, but he'll be hard-pressed to match Week 2's production, featuring three scores.
outlooksByWeek.4: James Cook will look to score in his third straight game when the Bills face the Ravens in Week 4. Cook is coming off a 15 touch, 87 total yard outing against Jacksonville in Week 3. It was his second straight game with just 11 carries, and he's been at a 50% snap share or fewer in each of the last two, a product of Buffalo having countless options that are rotating and not being force fed the ball. It's a challenging matchup with Baltimore allowing just 2.8 yards per carry, but Cook remains the unquestioned leader of the Bills backfield and his involvement in the passing game keeps him fantasy relevant.
outlooksByWeek.5: James Cook's rushes are trending in the wrong direction, but he should rebound in a Week 5 matchup with the Texans. Cook ran just nine times in Week 4, adding only one catch, both season lows. This was partly dictated by Buffalo falling behind big early, but it's a concerning trend. Look for the Bills to reestablish their run approach and for Cook to be featured. It's a solid bounce back spot where his fantasy managers should feel confident in placing him in their starting lineup, facing a defense surrendering a generous 4.7 yards per carry.
outlooksByWeek.6: James Cook's efficient usage is his greatest asset as he's coming off of a 22-touch outing in Week 5, despite a fourth-straight week where he's played 58% or fewer of the Bills offensive snaps. There's no reason to expect Cook's involvement to wane in Week 6's Monday night affair against the Jets, whose defense is yielding 4.2 yards per carry but is stingier against the pass. Cook remains a borderline RB1.
outlooksByWeek.7: James Cook hopes to return from a Week 6 absence due to a toe injury. Prior to his DNP, Cook collected double-digit touches in each of the Bills first five games, averaging a reasonable 4.4 yards per carry while scoring five times. Ray Davis impressed in Cook's absence, but assuming full health, Cook will lead this backfield in a Week 7 matchup against a Tennessee defense that's allowing 4.0 yards per carry, but only three rushing scores through five games.
outlooksByWeek.8: A touchdown salvaged James Cook's Week 7 fantasy scoring, as he otherwise went for a season-low 32 yards and 2.7 yards per carry while failing to record a reception. Cook still dominated snaps however, garnering a 54% share for the fourth time in six games. Buffalo travels to Seattle in Week 8, offering a chance to rebound against a defense that's allowing a generous 5.0 yards per carry, 146.1 yards per game with seven rushing scores in as many outings; Cook could flirt with RB1 territory as a result.
outlooksByWeek.9: Fresh of his first 100-yard rushing game of the season in Week 8, James Cook is surging. He's scored seven times in as many games, and despite Buffalo's renewed interest in throwing the ball, Cook has collected 32 touches over the last two weeks. His scoring prowess bodes well in a Week 9 matchup against a Dolphins defense that's allowed 10 rushing scores in seven games, along with 4.4 yards per carry in 2024.
outlooksByWeek.10: Despite garnering double-digit touches in every game this season, James Cook is turning into a touchdown dependent option for fantasy managers. He's scored seven times in eight games for the Bills, who are now more willing to pass often and while also showing a surprisingly willingness to rotate three backs more frequently in Week 9. It's cause for minor concern, but the three-man rotation is currently a one-week blip, and Cook should be trusted as a RB2 in Week 10 against a Colts defense that's allowing 4.4 yards per carry while knowing there likely isn't RB1 potential due to a lack of volume.
outlooksByWeek.11: After 19 carries for 80 yards and a touchdown in Week 10, James Cook has now scored nine times in as many games for the Bills while garnering at least 10 touches. Receiving usage has been sporadic but Cook remains the unquestioned leader of the backfield. A Week 11 matchup with the Chiefs doesn't immediately present with upside, as they're allowing only 3.6 yards per carry and just five touchdowns through nine games, but in a marquee matchup where stars shine, Cook's volume will have him firmly entrenched as an RB2 at minimum.
outlooksByWeek.13: Serving as the Bills' lead back, James Cook has been touchdown dependent through 10 games. He has rushed for 10 touchdowns while adding a score through the air, but five times has been limited to 44 yards or fewer. Cook and the Bills are coming off their bye. A Week 13 matchup against the 49ers awaits, facing a defense that's allowing 4.2 yards per carry and 16 rushing touchdowns, the third-highest total in the league, Cook is primed for more scoring opportunities, keeping him in high-end RB2 territory.
outlooksByWeek.14: James Cook emerged from the Bills' Week 12 bye looking rejuvenated, earning his second 100-yard outing of the season, rushing for 107 yards and a touchdown on 14 carries against the 49ers. Cook has scored 11 times in as many games despite QB Josh Allen continuing to score with his legs. Cook remains on track for his second 1,000-yard season. A Week 14 matchup with the Rams offers ample appeal against a defense that's allowing 4.6 yards per carry, but Cook will need to score again to reach RB1 returns.
outlooksByWeek.15: Game flow limited Cook's involvement in the Bills' Week 14 shootout, finishing with a season-low six carries and 20 yards while adding two catches for nine yards. It marked the second time in three games where Cook has finished with just 20 yards on the ground, and he hasn't played more than 46% of the team's snaps in three straight games. Another high scoring game could be on tap in Week 15 against Detroit, whose defense is allowing 4.4 yards per carry and 12 rushing scores in 13 games. Cook's managers likely don't have better alternatives, and it's always the right call to have shares of this offense, but no blame would be placed if fantasy players are nervous to put Cook in their Week 15 playoff lineups.

player.seasonOutlook: Cook returns to the gridiron for his third season with the Bills. He finished as RB12 in fantasy last season and ranked fourth in the league in rushing yards. Joe Brady replacing Ken Dorsey as offensive coordinator was a godsend for Cook. From Weeks 11 through 18, Cook averaged and impressive 19.6 touches and 16.4 fantasy points per game. Since Cook is the undisputed leader of the Bills' backfield, we can expect a similar workload from him in 2024. He can be safely drafted as a high-end RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jonnu Smith appears to be atop the depth chart for the Dolphins entering Week 1 against the Jaguars. Smith and Durham Smythe will likely share reps in this prolific offense that unfortunately doesn't lend itself to a plethora of targets to the position. Smith has three or more touchdowns in four of his seven seasons, and is coming off of a career-high 582 yards, but his opportunities in this offense likely make those numbers unrepeatable. Always a candidate to score, Smith faces a Jaguars defense that allowed the seventh-most passing touchdowns a year ago.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jonnu Smith will look for an elevated snap share in Week 2 for the Dolphins Thursday night against the Bills. Smith played just 18 snaps last week behind Durham Smythe, recording one catch on two targets. Smith figures to remain a red zone target, but the Dolphins pass tree goes straight through their two top receivers and their running backs, creating very minimal opportunity for Smith. Buffalo allowed six catches to tight ends last week, for only 35 yards.
outlooksByWeek.3: After drawing just two targets in the season opener, Smith logged seven targets on a 43% snap share in Week 2, resulting in six catches for 53 yards. Smith will look to build on an encouraging performance when the Dolphins face the Seahawks in Week 3. Game script could favor a busy afternoon for Smith with backup QB Sklyar Thompson expected to be at the helm with starting QB Tua Tagovailoa (concussion) likely sidelined. Even so, Smith is only in play for deeper formats.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jonnu Smith will seek a more consistent role in Week 4 when the Dolphins host the Titans on Monday night. Smith shined in Week Two with six catches on seven targets, but otherwise has just three grabs on five looks in two games. He'd appear to offer a safety valve underneath for whomever is under center for the Dolphins, but facing a Titans defense that's allowed the position to go for six catches and 40 yards through three games doesn't scream upside.
outlooksByWeek.5: Jonnu Smith was targeted just once last week and has logged three or fewer targets in three of four Dolphins games to date, catching two or fewer passes at the same rate. Week 5 offers optimism with a trip to New England facing a unit vulnerable to opposing tight ends. Even so, Smith is nothing more than a streaming option.
outlooksByWeek.7: Jonnu Smith went into the Dolphins Week 6 bye coming off his best game of the season, catching five of eight targets for 62 yards. While it marked his second game with at least five catches and 53 yards, Smith has not scored this season, had only three catches and 25 yards total in his other three games, and has not topped a 43% snap share. A Week 7 matchup against Indianapolis appears to make him touchdown dependent; they've allowed four scores to the position but held opposing tight ends for 43 yards or fewer in four of six games.
outlooksByWeek.8: Jonnu Smith has accrued 15 total targets over the past two games for the Dolphins despite not logging more than a 49% snap share. It's resulted in 12 catches, 158 yards and a touchdown, elite numbers for a tight end while the position hasn't been fruitful across the league. A Week 8 matchup with Arizona works in Smith's favor, as the Cardinals have allowed at least 51 yards to the position in three straight weeks and four of their last five, however the likely return of Tua Tagovailoa could dampen Smith's target share.
outlooksByWeek.9: Over the last three games, Jonnu Smith has amassed 21 targets, encouraging volume for a tight end in the 2024 landscape. That said, he turned six looks into only 20 yards (four catches) in Week 8 and Dolphins' quarterback Tua Tagovailoa hasn't historically frequented tight ends. A Week 9 matchup with the Bills profiles as boom or bust; their defense has allowed only one touchdown to the position through eight games, but 165 yards over the last two weeks.
outlooksByWeek.10: Continued volume has pushed Jonnu Smith into TE1 territory as the Dolphins enter Week 10. Regardless of who's been under center, Smith has at least six targets in four straight games, resulting in at least 46 yards in three games. He's scored just once and the ceiling remains low, but at a position with rare steady production, Smith merits consideration as a starter against a Rams defense  that's allowed four touchdowns and at least 40 yards to the position six times.
outlooksByWeek.11: Jonnu Smith continues to be a reliable tight end option for fantasy managers, catching three of his four targets for 45 yards in Week 10, the fourth time in five weeks with at least that yardage total. Drawing 31 targets for the Dolphins in that span, Smith will take aim at a Raiders defense in Week 11 that's allowed four touchdowns to the position over the last two weeks and 113 yards or more. Miami has ample mouths to feed, always creating risk for Smith's volume, but seemingly having a defined role, he slots as a Week 11 option.
outlooksByWeek.12: Coming off of a career high 101 yards and two touchdowns in Week 11, Jonnu Smith brings momentum into a Week 12 matchup against New England. Smith has at least four catches or 45 yards in six straight games for the Dolphins, collecting 39 targets in those outings. While a repeat performance shouldn't be expected, Smith has emerged as a viable option at tight end and should again be featured against a Patriots defense allowing the position to score in three of the last four weeks, though surrendering just 32 total yards over the last two outings.
outlooksByWeek.13: Jonnu Smith is surging for the Dolphins, amassing 19 targets over the last two weeks, producing 15 catches, 188 yards and three touchdowns. It's always best avoiding chasing prior totals, but at a position void of reliable options, Smith looks the part, gathering at least six targets in five of Miami's six games since a Week 6 bye. Green Bay awaits in Week 13, a defense that's allowed at least 42 yards to the position in nine of their 11 games, with three of their last six opponents registering 82 or more yards, landing Smith as a comfortable starter.
outlooksByWeek.14: Jonnu Smith is too hot to bench in advance of the Dolphins' Week 14 matchup against the Jets. Over the last three weeks, Smith has hauled in 25 passes on 30 targets, amassing 301 yards and three touchdowns. Having gone for 45 yards or more in eight of the Dolphins 12 games regardless of who was playing quarterback, Smith has to be trusted as a starting option in a bye-laden Week 14 despite the Jets having allowed the position to top 40 yards only four times all season.
outlooksByWeek.15: Overtime rescued Jonnu Smith's fantasy day in Week 14, where he finished with three catches, 44 yards and a touchdown, all of which came in the extra stanza. While the outing marked a six-week low in yardage, Smith has now scored four times in as many games for the Dolphins. A Week 15 matchup at Houston presents a defense that's allowed the position to post at least 55 yards in four straight, while scoring twice, putting Smith on fantasy radars. Miami has thrown 40-plus times in three straight, and it's funneled through four options, suggesting opportunities will remain plentiful.

player.seasonOutlook: Smith, now in his eighth season and first with the Dolphins, joins an offense that ranked third in total yards per game last season. While Tua Tagovailoa led the league in passing, the majority of the yards came from Tyreek Hill and Jaylen Waddle. With Hill and Waddle projected to continue as the primary targets, Smith's fantasy prospects are limited, especially considering the Dolphins' strong running game with De'Von Achane and Raheem Mostert, who will score a fair share of touchdowns. Given the returning key playmakers for 2024, fantasy managers should consider Smith as no more than a TE3.

The Bills D/ST finished 2023 as the No. 5 D/ST, thanks to finishing sixth in interceptions (18), fifth in fumbles recovered, and fourth in sacks. Buffalo also held opponents to only 310.9 total yards per game, the eighth fewest in the league, and ranked fourth in points allowed per game (18.3). Head coach Sean McDermott is a defensive guru and, while the Bills have had a top defensive unit for years, injuries and aging players have slowed the unit down and led to a bit of an offseason exodus of talent. With the likes of Micah Hyde, Jordan Poyer, Tre'Davious White and Leonard Floyd done, Buffalo's D/ST is now more of a fringe starting option.

outlooksByWeek.1: C.J. Stroud's sophomore season begins on the road against the AFC South rival Colts in Week 1. Stroud threw for 4,108 yards with a 23:5 TD:INT in a highly successful rookie regular season for the Texans after being selected second overall in the 2023 NFL Draft. That success included 648 yards and a 4:0 TD:INT in two games against the Colts, whom the Texans beat on the road in Week 18 last season with a playoff berth on the line. Houston traded for six-time 1,000-yard receiver Stefon Diggs while bringing back its top three receiving yards leaders from last season (WRs Nico Collins and Tank Dell, plus TE Dalton Schultz). Indianapolis allowed the fifth-most points per game last season (24.4) and didn't make significant personnel changes on defense, bringing back all 10 players that made double-digit starts on that side of the ball.
outlooksByWeek.2: C.J. Stroud will face a stingy Bears secondary in Week 2 after leading the Texans to victory with a pair of touchdown passes in the season opener. Both of Stroud's scoring strikes went to offseason addition Stefon Diggs, who forms one of the league's most potent wide receiver trios alongside Nico Collins and Tank Dell. The Bears limited Will Levis to just 127 passing yards with a 1:2 TD:INT in Week 1, but Stroud figures to have much more success considering he has a career average of 271.4 passing yards per game while fellow 2023 draft pick Levis has averaged 193.5 passing yards per game. Stroud had a 17:4 TD:INT at home last season compared to a 6:1 mark on the road, and this will be Houston's home opener.
outlooksByWeek.3: C.J. Stroud has a 3:0 TD:INT heading into a Week 3 clash between the undefeated Texans and Vikings. He hasn't thrown an interception in any of his nine NFL starts, including the playoffs. Minnesota has been more vulnerable to the pass than the run, but defensive coordinator Brian Flores' unit is allowing just 11.5 points per game. Flores will have some tricks up his sleeve as he tries to contain Stroud, but the 2023 Offensive Rookie of the Year has an elite receiving corps at his disposal in Nico Collins, Stefon Diggs and Tank Dell, though the Texans may be without starting RB Joe Mixon (ankle). Collins leads the NFL with 252 receiving yards, accounting for over half of Stroud's 494 passing yards.
outlooksByWeek.4: C.J. Stroud had just the second multi-interception game of his excellent young career in the Week 3 loss to Minnesota, but Houston's second-year quarterback has a nice Week 4 bounce-back opportunity against the 0-3 Jaguars. Despite working with an improved wide receiver room, Stroud's averaging just 236.3 passing yards per game in 2024 after leading the NFL with 273.9 passing yards per game in 2023. Jacksonville's surrendering 28.3 points per game, so Stroud's safely in the QB1 range for Week 4.
outlooksByWeek.5: C.J. Stroud is 8-2 with a 20:4 TD:INT at home in his career, and Houston's talented young QB will look to keep rolling in Week 5 against a Bills defense that surrendered 35 points in Baltimore in Week 4 after limiting its previous two opponents to 10 points apiece. Stroud bounced back from a poor Week 3 showing in Minnesota by throwing for 345 yards and two TDs in a 24-20 Week 4 home win over the Jaguars. He'll be a fantasy QB1 as usual in Week 5, while Nico Collins and Stefon Diggs should continue to work as Stroud's top two targets, and Houston will welcome back No. 3 WR Tank Dell (chest) after a one-game absence.
outlooksByWeek.6: C.J. Stroud combined to throw for 676 yards in Weeks 4 and 5, but he could be without top target Nico Collins (hamstring) for the Texans' Week 6 trip to New England. Collins leads the NFL with 567 receiving yards, but Stroud still has enough playmakers at his disposal to be effective against a Patriots secondary that has allowed over 250 passing yards per game but only a 4:2 TD:INT. Houston is heavily favored and could lean more on the running game while playing with the lead, especially if starting RB Joe Mixon (ankle) returns, but Stroud's fantasy managers can safely deploy him as they usually would.
outlooksByWeek.7: C.J. Stroud threw for at least 300 yards or three TDs in three consecutive starts Weeks 4-6 after hitting neither milestone in Weeks 1-3. The Texans will be without top WR Nico Collins (hamstring) for a second consecutive game in Week 7 against the Packers, but Stroud still has WRs Stefon Diggs and Tank Dell at his disposal. Green Bay's opportunistic defense has excelled at causing turnovers, but the Packers have been among the most generous secondaries in terms of passing yards (1,491) and passing TDs (10) allowed to QBs, so Stroud's a set-and-forget fantasy starter for Week 7.
outlooksByWeek.8: C.J. Stroud's momentum was stunted in a Week 7 loss to the Packers, as he threw for just 86 yards without a TD after three consecutive starts with at least 300 yards or three TDs. Despite the continued absence of top target Nico Collins (hamstring), Stroud has a nice opportunity to get back on track when the Texans return home to host the Colts in Week 8. Stroud has 21 touchdown passes in 11 career home games compared to only 12 TDs in 11 road games, and Indianapolis is allowing 382 scrimmage yards per game. Continue to start Stroud in fantasy if you have him.
outlooksByWeek.9: C.J. Stroud will be without Nico Collins (hamstring) and now won't have Stefon Diggs (knee) either for Thursday's Week 9 at the Jets. Diggs was placed on IR and is out for the season. Stroud was limited to 91 passing yards by the Jets' defense last season, and Houston will likely ride Joe Mixon and the running game with the team's receivers banged up against a defense that has been much worse against the run than the pass. While Stroud's talented enough to start in fantasy regardless of situation, his floor is much lower than usual in Week 9, so managers in shallow leagues should consider alternatives.
outlooksByWeek.10: C.J. Stroud could get top WR Nico Collins (hamstring) back for the first time since Week 5 when the Texans host the Lions on Sunday Night Football in Week 10. Collins was leading the NFL with 567 receiving yards prior to going on IR, so his return would help make up for the absence of Stefon Diggs, who suffered a season-ending knee injury in Week 8. Stroud's averaging an impressive 308.9 passing yards per game at home in his career, with a 22:5 TD:INT in 12 home games, but he'd be just a borderline QB1 for fantasy purposes if Collins remains unavailable against a Lions defense that has held QBs to a 6:11 TD:INT this season.
outlooksByWeek.11: C.J. Stroud has had an up and down season, and he has hit a rough patch with a 2:2 TD:INT in Weeks 7-10. The potential return of top WR Nico Collins (hamstring) could help Stroud get back on track in Week 11 against the struggling Cowboys, as Stroud's recent struggles have come while working with a depleted Texans receiving corps. Dallas is allowing 34.5 points per game during its four-game losing streak.
outlooksByWeek.12: C.J. Stroud has slumped to a 2:3 TD:INT from Week 7 onward while averaging just 210.2 passing yards per game during that five-game span. It won't be easy to rebound in Week 12, as the Texans are likely to ride Joe Mixon's legs more than Stroud's arm against a Titans defense that's allowing a league-low 164.6 passing yards per game. Stroud's fantasy managers should consider streaming an alternative QB option in a more favorable matchup.
outlooksByWeek.13: C.J. Stroud posted his fourth multi-TD passing performance of the season in Week 12 against the Titans, but he still has an ugly 4:5 TD:INT from Week 7 onward. Houston's struggling QB has an excellent opportunity to bust out of his slump in Week 13 against a Jaguars defense that has surrendered a 23:5 TD:INT this season. Those 23 passing TDs allowed are second-most in the NFL, so fantasy managers who have been waiting for Stroud to get back into the fantasy QB1 range are likely to get their wish.
outlooksByWeek.15: C.J. Stroud brings a 15:9 TD:INT into a Week 15 home game against the Dolphins, having taken a step back after posting a 23:5 TD:INT as a rookie last season. Miami has limited QBs to a 14:7 TD:INT but just allowed Aaron Rodgers to throw for a season-high 339 yards in Week 14 while Stroud and the Texans were on bye. With star WR Nico Collins at full strength and ready to lead the passing game, Stroud's a low-end fantasy starter for Week 15 despite the sophomore QB's up-and-down play.

player.seasonOutlook: The former Buckeye looks to build on a momentous first season that included becoming just the fifth rookie quarterback to ever throw for at least 4,000 yards. Without much rushing volume or success in either his collegiate or professional profile, Stroud's fantasy production will be defined by his proficiency from the pocket. After finishing seventh in per-game fantasy output last season, another prolific passing season could unfold given the presence of a trio of talented receivers -- Nico Collins, Stefon Diggs and Tank Dell -- each of whom brings special route trees and skill sets to the field. Securing Stroud in the middle rounds is a sound strategy for those who wait a bit at the position.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jared Goff enters the season having finished 2023 as a top-seven fantasy QB last year, benefiting from a high-volume Lions passing offense led by offensive coordinator Ben Johnson. Goff faces the Rams on Sunday Night Football in Week 1, a rematch of last year's Wild Card game. Despite a low average depth of target, Goff's efficiency and volume make him a strong fantasy play. The Rams allowed the seventh-most fantasy points per game to quarterbacks last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jared Goff struggled at times in the Lions' 26-20 overtime win against the Rams, completing 18 of 28 passes for 217 yards with one touchdown and one interception. His lone score came on a 52-yard deep shot to Jameson Williams, but a fourth-quarter interception stalled a potential game-sealing drive. Goff did manage to rally the Lions, helping set up a game-tying field goal in the final seconds before Detroit's rushing attack secured the win in overtime. Looking ahead to Week 2, Goff will face a Buccaneers defense that allowed the fourth-most passing yards in the NFL last season (248.9 per game). Tampa Bay's secondary was also hit hard by injuries last week, potentially creating a favorable scenario for Goff to rebound from his uneven season opener.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jared Goff will look to turn things around in Week 3 as the Lions face the Cardinals on the road. Goff struggled in last week's loss to the Buccaneers despite 55 pass attempts, finishing with 307 yards but no touchdowns and two interceptions. He has a chance to improve on his 6.3 yards per attempt this season, the lowest since his rookie year in 2016, against an Arizona defense allowing 9.0 yards per pass attempt, the second-highest mark in the NFL. Detroit's top receiver, Amon-Ra St. Brown, is questionable with a leg injury, but Goff has ample firepower around him to potentially put up better numbers against a somewhat porous pass defense.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jared Goff is averaging 241.0 passing yards with an uncharacteristic 3:4 TD:INT through three contests. The Lions' signal caller has exceeded 30 pass attempts in just one game this season, after averaging 35.6 attempts last year. Goff may continue to struggle in Week 4 against the Seahawks, who rank third in fantasy points allowed to opposing quarterbacks, although they've benefited from facing Bo Nix, Jacoby Brissett, and a combination of Skylar Thompson and Tim Boyle in their first three games. Seattle's defense also leads the NFL, surrendering just 4.7 yards per pass attempt this season.
outlooksByWeek.6: Jared Goff and the Lions, fresh off a bye, will look to stay hot against the Cowboys in Week 6. When last on the field, Goff set an NFL record in a Monday night win over Seattle, when he completed 18 of 18 pass attempts for 292 yards with two touchdowns, without an interception. Goff became the first QB in NFL history to finish with a perfect completion percentage on more than 10 attempts and with over 200 passing yards, and that's discounting the fact that he caught a seven-yard touchdown pass on his only target. Detroit's passing game had gotten off to a slow start, but Goff's immaculate Week 4 performance could be a real sign of better things to come, especially if OC Ben Johnson can hone in on some scheme adjustments during the bye. Goff is coming off back-to-back games with two passing touchdowns, and he'll get the benefit of facing a Cowboys defense that will be without DeMarcus Lawrence, and likely also Micah Parsons.
outlooksByWeek.7: Jared Goff will look to stay hot as the Lions prepare for a key Week 7 divisional matchup against the undefeated Vikings. In his last three appearances, Goff has thrown seven passing touchdowns and just one interception, while averaging 268 yards per game. Detroit has remained firmly in command of their most recent two games, against the Seahawks and Cowboys, having scored 40-plus points in each contest. A willingness to spread the ball around to a multitude of playmakers, deploy trick plays, and lean on what's been an unstoppable backfield dupe of David Montgomery and Jahmyr Gibbs has allowed Goff to thrive, especially with Jameson Williams having emerged as a true big-play threat to complement No. 1 receiver Amon-Ra St. Brown. Goff has thrown multiple scores in three straight contests and boasts a tremendous 12.2 yards per pass attempt in that span, but he now faces the task of overcoming a Minnesota defense on the road that ranks sixth best in the NFL in terms of YPA allowed to opposing QBs.
outlooksByWeek.8: Jared Goff and the Lions will look to stay hot heading into a Week 8 home game against the Titans. The veteran pocket passer has been elite in terms of efficiency to begin the 2024 season, a fact that was fully on display during Detroit's 31-29 win over the Vikings. Goff completed 22 of 25 passes for 280 yards with two touchdowns and no interception, a near-perfect performance against what's been a stellar Minnesota defense. He did, however, commit two fumbles, losing one. Now, with a home matchup against the 1-5 Titans on deck, Goff and the Lions' offense are in prime position to keep up their momentum.
outlooksByWeek.9: Jared Goff and the Lions will work to continue flying high heading into a Week 9 divisional matchup against the Packers. Heading on the road to Green Bay, Detroit's unbelievable offensive momentum makes the team a solid favorite, and doubly so in the event that Jordan Love's groin injury limits him or holds him out entirely. Goff, meanwhile, has led the most efficient offense in the NFL in recent weeks, as the Lions are coming off a season-best 52 points in a Week 8 blowout win over Tennessee. Detroit has averaged an unbelievable 43 points in their last four games, with Goff boasting 10 touchdowns and 0 interceptions in that span. As long as the Lions are firing on all cylinders, there may be no defense in the league truly equipped to deal with Goff, even despite No. 2 wide receiver Jameson Williams being out one more game due to a suspension.
outlooksByWeek.10: Jared Goff and the Lions will look to keep rolling on the road against Houston in Week 10. Despite a rainy, exposed road environment, Goff managed the team to a convincing 24-14 win over the Packers. He finished with a modest statline, completing 18 of 22 passes for 145 yards, one touchdown and zero interceptions, but a mistake-free game was all Detroit truly needed to secure a win with Green Bay's receiving corps being plagued by drops. Though Goff is now coming off his first game without multiple TDs since Week 2, his immediate prospects look optimistic as ever, heading into a dome game against a Texans secondary allowing the second-most passing TDs per game to opponents. Detroit's offense had averaged an unbelievable 43 points in four contests prior to the rainy win over Green Bay, and should be on track to pick up where it left off with Goff at the helm Week 10.
outlooksByWeek.11: Jared Goff and the Lions' offense will look to clean up their act on the road against Jacksonville in Week 11. Despite a sloppy effort from Goff, Detroit was able to escape with a 26-23 win over Houston, but the franchise quarterback displayed a worrying capacity to melt down that hadn't been seen with his newest team. In what was certainly his worst performance in a Lions uniform, Goff threw a career-high five INTs, more picks than he'd thrown across eight previous starts this season. He likewise finished with just a 50 percent completion rate (15 of 30) and 240 yards, with his two touchdowns barely mitigating the damage done by the ridiculous five turnovers. The Lions remain convincingly atop the NFC, and a matchup against the crumbling Jaguars shouldn't provide much difficulty, but Goff will need to clean things up before a looming late-season gauntlet. Matchups against the Packers, Bills, Bears, 49ers and Vikings will be on deck for Detroit to close out the regular season.
outlooksByWeek.12: Jared Goff will look to keep up his momentum coming off a four-TD game as the Lions head to Indianapolis in Week 12. In beating up on a hapless Jacksonville secondary, Goff threw 412 yards with four touchdowns and no interceptions to lead Detroit to a 52-6 win, earning himself a perfect passer rating. In his last eight appearances Goff has now thrown multiple touchdowns on seven occasions, and he logged season-high totals versus the Jaguars in terms of both passing yards and TDs. The 9-1 Lions have shown a willingness to run up the scoreboard against lesser opponents, with four 40-plus point games so far this season, and Goff's next matchup will come against a Colts secondary that ranks 26th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.13: Jared Goff and the 1st place Lions will look to keep rolling versus the Bears in a Week 13 matchup on Thanksgiving. Detroit was able to safely lean on Jahmyr Gibbs and the rushing game in a seamless 24-6 win over the Colts, but Goff was still productive, completing 26 of 36 pass attempts for 269 yards, without any touchdowns or interceptions. All three of the Lions' scores came on the ground, with Gibbs (12 carries for 93 yards) accounting for two, and David Montgomery (eight rushes for 37 yards) getting into the end zone once. The offense could deploy a similar recipe against Chicago, who have allowed the third-fewest passing touchdowns and just limited Justin Jefferson to two catches for 27 yards. The Bears are more vulnerable against the run, ranking just 20th, so keeping the ball out of Goff's hands and prioritizing the involvement of Gibbs and Montgomery, one of the league's best thunder-lightning duos, could be Detroit's safest bet.
outlooksByWeek.14: Jared Goff and the Lions will look to continue rolling heading into another divisional Thursday contest, this time Week 14 against the Packers. The veteran signal-caller tossed two more TDs during Detroit's narrow win over Chicago on Thanksgiving, both to TE Sam LaPorta, bringing his total to 22 touchdowns and just nine interceptions. At 11-1, the Lions remain powerhouses of the NFC, but it was notable to see the Bears come within a botched time management scenario of sending the Thanksgiving Day contest to overtime. That Detroit had to eke out a win can be largely blamed on Goff and the offense petering out after the third quarter, so getting back on track versus Green Bay will be crucial.
outlooksByWeek.15: Jared Goff and the Lions, at 12-1, will look to keep rolling at home against the Bills in Week 15. Fresh off a narrow 34-31 win over the Packers on Thursday Night Football, in which he threw for 283 yards, three touchdowns and just one interception, Goff now boasts a 25:10 TD:INT on the season. His connection with star wideout Amon-Ra St. Brown was off versus Green Bay, as the No. 1 receiver secured five of six targets for just 34 yards, without a touchdown. Still, Detroit's offense has proven replete of playmakers, as Tim Patrick stepped up with six catches for 43 yards and two scores on seven targets, while TE Sam LaPorta (5-54-0) and WR Jameson Williams (5-80-0) also stepped up under pressure. In what may portend a future Super Bowl matchup, Goff and the Lions will next face the task of taking down the 10-3 Bills.

player.seasonOutlook: Jared Goff returns as the Lions' starter after his best season in the Motor City. In 2023, he was second in passing yards, attempts and completions, and fourth in passing TDs. In fact, Goff is the only QB to have at least 4,400 passing yards and 29 passing TDs in each of the past two seasons. However, he offers virtually zero in the rushing department (94 total rushing yards over that same two-season span). As a result, Goff finished 10 weeks as QB12 or lower in fantasy points despite his passing prowess and Detroit's high-octane offense. Goff is best viewed as a mid-range QB2 in Detroit's run-first scheme.
